<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 11 Farmers Killed in Egypt's Road Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Eleven farm workers were killed
when a trailer-tractor they were travelling veered off a road and
plunged into a canal north of Cairo today, police sources said.
</P>
<P>
Two others were badly injured as the trailer taking the 13
workers to pick cotton overturned near the town of Sanbalawin in
the Nile Delta about 65 kilometers north of Cairo. One of the dead
was a 14-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
It was the third such fatal incident in less than a month that
people were killed on their way to work in cotton fields.
</P>
<P>
On September 16, 29 children were killed and 54 others injured
when their truck swerved off a road and overturned into a canal
north of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The children, aged between 14-17, worked as spare hands in the
government-owned cotton fields.
</P>
<P>
On October 1, 30 children were drowned in a similar accident as
the tractor carrying them to cotton fields in Assuit, southern
Egypt, ran off a slippery road into a canal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Government Backs Report on Quality Education: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Education and Manpower
Secretary Joseph W.P. Wong of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR) government said today that the government supports
the Report of the Education Commission (EC) on Quality School
Education.
</P>
<P>
Expressing gratitude to the EC of the government for drawing up
wide-ranging recommendations after a thorough study of the issue,
Wong said, "The government supports the main thrust of the
report, which is to devolve more authority and responsibility to
schools and promote bottom-up initiatives for the school sector."
</P>
<P>
"The government will announce its decisions on the subject as
soon as possible," Wong told reporters, right after EC Chairman
Rosie Young announced the release of the report at a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the news conference on the release of the report,
Young said the EC has fully considered the public views collected
during the consultation from November 1996 to January 1997 in
finalizing its recommendations in the report.
</P>
<P>
The report "focuses on ways to improve school management and
performance toward the provision of quality school education to
better meet the needs of students," Young said.
</P>
<P>
Young stressed that educational aims should be translated into
quality indicators, to be developed by schools with assistance
from the government's Education Department.
</P>
<P>
"To effectively enhance the quality of school education, a
quality assurance mechanism should be put in place. We welcome the
Education Department's plan to adopt a 'whole-school' approach to
quality assurance inspection, and recommend that quality
assurance within schools should be achieved through school-based
management, self-evaluation, and cooperation between schools and
parents," Young said.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that all schools should practice school-based
management by the year 2000, Young said: "I urge the government to
accept the recommendations of the report and set aside adequate
resources for implementation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
