<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian PM Specifies Areas of Cooperation With S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister
Inder Kumar Gujral today specified fields of cooperation with
South Africa, the South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Time has come for the two countries to build "a rapidly
growing super structure of cooperation," Gujral told South
African parliament in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
He said India can profit from South Africa's skills and
technology in the fields of mining and infrastructure
development.
</P>
<P>
India, in turn, can be of special help in the development of
small scale industries, the housing sector, human resource
development, employment-generation programs and in science and
technology as well.
</P>
<P>
A second area of great importance, he said, was the
strengthening of joint endeavors in regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We see South Africa as a bridgehead into the markets of
southern Africa and we can play the same role for your country as
a spring board into South Asia and beyond," Gujral told South
African parliamentarians.
</P>
<P>
He called on both countries to play a definitive role in
strengthening the Indian Ocean rim cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The two countries head the Indian Ocean Rim Alliance for
Regional Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He also called for greater cooperation between the two
countries in world forums such as the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM)
and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
He said the NAM is still necessary to address problems facing
the developing world.
</P>
<P>
On United Nations reform, Gujral said both countries have an
important responsibility to help reform the global organization,
especially its Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, the two leaders presided over the signing of
three agreements in geology and mining resources, tourism, and
science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Indo-South African relations saw rapid development in recent
years. The two countries agreed to establish a "strategic
partnership" in the Red Ford Declaration signed by Mandela and
then Indian prime minister Deve Gowda during Mandela's visit to
India in March this year.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade grew to over 600 million U.S. Dollars last
year from some 80 million U.S. Dollars in 1993. Gujral predicted
that the figure could reach one billion by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Gujral's visit to South Africa, which is the first by an
Indian prime minister, was given special significance because
this year is also the 50th anniversary of India's independence
from Britain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lithuanian FM Defends Effort to Join NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Lithuanian Foreign
Minister Algirdas Saudargas said here today that his country's
efforts to enter NATO do not contradict with its friendship with
Russia.
</P>
<P>
Saudargas, who arrived here Monday, made the remarks at a
joint press conference after holding talks with his Hungarian
counterpart Kovacs Laszlo.
</P>
<P>
Lithuania's geo-political situation is similar to that of
Poland, he said, adding that his country can not fully understand
Russia's worries about the Lithuanian intention to join the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
The NATO summit held in Madrid in July decided to invite
Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic to join the alliance.
</P>
<P>
However, Russia has been strongly opposing NATO's eastward
expansion, saying the expansion is a threat to Russia's security
and is likely to stir up a fresh confrontation.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Saudargas also called on the European
Union (EU) to send officials to Lithuania for an on-the-spot
investigation.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the EU will decide at its December meeting to
invite Lithuania to join the union.
</P>
<P>
Laszlo said on the same occasion that Hungary is willing to
share its experience with Lithuania in its application for the
NATO membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Strengthen Ties With Azerbaijan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov said today in Azerbaijan's capital city of Baku that
Azerbaijan is one of the countries that have Russia's priority in
its foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Azerbaijan President Geidar Aliyev,
Primakov said that the Russian-Azerbaijan relations should be
pushed forward and there is no major obstacle on the way ahead,
the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Primakov called for resolving the problems in the ties between
the two countries through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Russia signed a friendship and cooperation treaty with Armenia
on August 29. The treaty had worried Azerbaijan, which has been
locked in a row with Armenia over the disputed region of
Nagorno-Karabakh.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said the Russian-Armenian treaty was not directed
against any other countries including Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
Primakov arrived here today for a brief visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
