<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Tobacco Farmers Complain of Levies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's tobacco farmers this
year forked out over 430 million Zimbabwe Dollars (34 million
U.S. Dollars) to the government under the controversial 10
percent levy on them, the Commercial Farmers Union (CFU) said
today.
</P>
<P>
The levy has brought a heavy burden to growers and merchants
of the golden leaf, added the CFU.
</P>
<P>
CFU Director David Hasluck said heavy rains during the 1996/97
season meant that both tobacco output and revenue were lower than
anticipated.
</P>
<P>
"The amount paid by farmers this year in tobacco levies is
about 438 million Zimbabwe Dollars which, however, has pulled
most large scale commercial farmers deeper into debt," he warned.
</P>
<P>
Initial crop estimates put this year's flue-cured tobacco
output at 205 million Kilograms, but heavy rains experienced
during the early part of the year saw production tumbling to 186
million KG, earning the country about five billion Zimbabwe
Dollars (400 million U.S. Dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
The levy, shared equally between growers and merchants, was
introduced in July last year under heavy protests from the
large-scale farming community.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco is Zimbabwe's biggest foreign currency earner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
