<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC to Launch Military Cooperation Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The six Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) members said in Doha, Qatar today that they will
launch two military cooperation projects in "a very near future."
</P>
<P>
A statement issued to reporters after the 15th annual meeting
of the GCC chiefs of staff said the projects are aimed at
"tightening (military) cooperation and communications safety."
</P>
<P>
No details about the two projects were given. However, the
military leaders said the projects were initiated "a long time
ago" but kept hanged up.
</P>
<P>
"They are very important projects in the framework of the
(GCC) military cooperation process. It is the outcome of old
studies which just yielded fruits at this meeting," General al
Raken Hamad bin Ali al Atuiya, Qatar's Chief of Staff said
in the statement.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting took place in coincidence with a joint GCC
naval exercises off the coast of Bahrain which started on Saturday
and lasts for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Qatari news agency said that during the meeting, the GCC
chiefs of staff discussed the latest developments in the region,
but they declined to to make public comments.
</P>
<P>
"We have discussed issues related to regional security, but we
would not talked about the political matters because they should
be left to politicians," Atuiya said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Qatari general said "The GCC members would jointly
face any kind of threat to them."
</P>
<P>
He also added that the GCC states always "attach great
importance to developing their armed forces."
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that he and other GCC chiefs of staff have agreed
to hold joint air exercises, but said they have not decided
whether foreign participation should be invited.
</P>
<P>
"This thing will be submitted to (GCC) defense ministers. They
will make decisions. We just agreed to hold the exercises and
intensify them," said Atuiya.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a political, economic and military alliance, was set
up in 1980. It groups Bahrain, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Oman
and the UAE. They also set up a collective troops named Peninsula
Shield in the early 1990 as a major step to boost military
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
However, due to relatively limited human resources, the GCC
countries still remained seriously reliant on a large foreign
presence, particularly that of the U.S. and its western allies
to protect their security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
