<HEADLINE> Swazi Journalists Protest Media Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Journalists in Swaziland
today marched to the prime minister's office in Mbabane to
protest against a media control bill approved by the government,
reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Swazi Information and Broadcasting Minister Muntu Mswane had
drafted the bill after complaints in parliament of a lack of
professionalism in the local media, and of "irresponsbile and
sensational" reporting.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which was approved recently by the government and
soon to be tabled in parliament, stipulates that journalists
found to have committed a serious breach could be ordered to
issue a retraction, publish an apology or be deregistered,
said South African press reports.
</P>
<P>
Journalists who fail to comply could then face a fine of up to
15,000 Rand (3,200 U.S, Dollars) or five years' imprisonment and
the publication a fine of up to 100,000 Rand (21,000 U.S.
Dollars).
</P>
<P>
President of the Swaziland National Association of Journalists
Mbuso Mkhatjwa read a statement, demanding the immediate
withdrawal of the bill.
</P>
<P>
Journalists in Swaziland believed there is a need for more
responsible reporting but through self-censorship and that
guidelines should be drawn by the media houses themselves in
consultation with the government, Mkhatjwa said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
