<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Try Former Vichy Official for Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 7 (Xinhua) -- France will put on trial Wednesday
a former Gaullist minister and senior official under the Vichy
collaboration regime during World War II, Maurice Papon, for the
arrest and deportation of some 1,500 Jews from 1942 to 1944.
</P>
<P>
This will be the last trial of a Frenchman for crimes against
humanity, after two other historic trials were staged by France
against the former Gestapo chief of Lyon, Klaus Barbie, in 1987,
and against former Lyon militiamen chief Paul Touvier in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Both Barbie and Touvier were convicted of crimes against
humanity and were given life imprisonment sentences. Both of them
had died.
</P>
<P>
Except the extreme-right National Front, nearly all French
political parties welcomed the decision made by a court in
Bordeaux, capital of the Prefecture of Gironde, where Papon served
as secretary general during the war under the Vichy regime.
</P>
<P>
Papon was sent to a prison in Bordeaux today from his home in
Gretz-Armainvilliers outside Paris on the eve of the first day of
his trial.
</P>
<P>
The 87-year-old former Vichy official, who later served as
cabinet minister and Paris police chief under President Charles de
Gaulle and President Valery Giscard d'Estaing, issued a defiant
statement calling his trial "an until now prefabricated trial "
and "unworthy sham of a state of law."
</P>
<P>
He called on the judges to work with "independence and
impartiality" over his case, and denounced the French government
for trying to "illustrate and confirm the preferred official
declarations on `a guilty France'" based on its collaboration
with Nazi Germany during World War II.
</P>
<P>
He was apparently referring to a declaration made in 1995 by
President Jacques Chirac, who officially recognized for the first
time since the end of the war that France made a "collective
fault" by deporting 76,000 Jews to Nazi death camps.
</P>
<P>
Chirac's predecessor, Francois Mitterrand, said that the French
nation or the French republic had not participated in what he
called "the sad adventure of the Vichy government" and therefore
should not be held responsible for the deportation of Jews.
</P>
<P>
"The France of depth should pull itself together so that I
could face an independent and impartial justice," said Papon.
</P>
<P>
Former Gaullist Interior Minister Charles Pasqua has warned
against making Papon into a "scapegoat" for the Vichy period,
while the president of the National Front Jean-Marie Le Pen
described the trial as "absolutely absurd." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
