<HEADLINE> China on Course for Sustainable Growth: HSBC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- China's economic expansion
remained firm in the second quarter driven by strong growth in
exports, said the Global Outlook quarterly of HSBC Group.
</P>
<P>
Real GDP growth in the first half was 9.5 percent and aggregate
demand is expected to remain strong in the second half on the back
of slower, but still strong, net export growth and strong
underlying investment demand, it added.
</P>
<P>
On its research paper "On Course For Sustainable Growth"
published today, HSBC said China's inflation fell to a six-year
low in the second quarter with disinflation now appearing in
several sectors of the economy.
</P>
<P>
The paper stressed that coupled with still strong economic
growth, however, disinflation in China is simply a healthy
adjustment to previous over-expansion and not an indication of an
imminent recession.
</P>
<P>
It expected that with the Chinese government sticking to its
tight monetary policy, inflation was 3.9 percent in the first half
and should average 4.0 percent for 1997, down from 8.3 percent in
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
