<HEADLINE> Currency Notes Redemption Issued in Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The National Bank of
Ethiopia issued today a legal tender currency notes redemption
directive.
</P>
<P>
According to the directive signed by Governor Dubale Jale,
currency notes issued by the bank prior to a date to be notified
to the public by the bank shall be exchanged at the rate of one
Birr equals one Birr of the new notes.
</P>
<P>
"Amounts appearing in any law in Ethiopia, contract, sale,
payment, bill, note, instrument and security for money and every
transaction dealing in Birr before the coming into force of these
directives shall be converted at the rate of one Birr equals one
Birr," the directive said.
</P>
<P>
The directive said the new currency notes are 100, 50, 10, 5,
and 1 Birr respectively.
</P>
<P>
It further said redemable currency notes shall cease to be
legal tender after 50 days from the date to be fixed and
disclosed in advance to the public by the bank.
</P>
<P>
According to the directive, lawfully issued coins presently in
circulation in Ethiopia are not affected by the issuance of these
directives.
</P>
<P>
The issuance of new currency notes was announced by President
Negasso Gidada at parliament meeting here yesterday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
