<HEADLINE> S. Leone Military Accused of Using Nerve Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The military junta in Sierra
Leone was today accused of attacking the west African
peacekeeping force (ECOMOG) with nerve gas.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG troops, who are carrying out an economic embargo on
Sierra Leone as mandated by sub-regional leaders, were receiving
instructions on how to survive the gas, Nigeria's defense
spokesman Godwin Ugbo said here today.
</P>
<P>
"I learned they are educating our our troops on how to
overcome the effect of the gas," he said, restating that ECOMOG,
led by Nigeria, was not in Sierra Leone to fight.
</P>
<P>
Nerve gas is a kind of biological weapon used in warefare to
make the emeny weak, dizzy and worn-out. It was used during the
Gulf War and many veterans are currently suffering its effects.
</P>
<P>
The acting director of defense information also dismissed
allegations that ECOMOG was attacking the junta positions with
Scud missiles, A Soviet-made long-range weapon used by Iraqi
forces during the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
"Nigerian does not have such a weapon and no country in the
sub-region has it," Ugbo said.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that ships coming to dock in the Sierra Leonean
capital Freetown would continue to be searched by ECOMOG forces,
except those carrying food and medical supplies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
