<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daimler-Benz to Switch to Euro in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Germany's largest industrial group
Daimler-Benz AG announced today that it has decided to introduce
the single European currency, the Euro, as its "corporate
currency" from January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Under a decision made today by the board of management of
Daimler-Benz, the Euro will replace the German mark as the
company's standard monetary unit for all relevant business
transactions from January 1, 1999, the start-up date of the Euro.
</P>
<P>
The board also decided that the company's business results for
the first half of 1999 are to be drawn up in the Euro. Its
customers will also be able to choose Euro or their national
currency to pay their bills on a voluntary basis during the
transition period of the Euro from 1999 to 2002.
</P>
<P>
"Our decision is basically a signal for our customers,
suppliers and partners in industry and public administration that
we see a tremendous chance both for Europe and our group in the
European Monetary Union," said Daimler-Benz Chairman Juergen
Schrempp.
</P>
<P>
Under the Euro timetable, the conversion to the single currency
will not be compulsory in its member states until January 2002,
when the Euro banknotes and coins are officially introduced after
a three-year transition period during which the Euro will only be
used in cashless transactions.
</P>
<P>
By deciding to convert to the Euro as early as January 1999,
Daimler-Benz is one of the first German companies to take such a
step at this early stage.
</P>
<P>
Daimler-Benz Chief Financial Officer Manfred Gentz estimated
the company's costs for the currency conversion at about 200
million marks (114 million U.S. dollars), with more than half of
the money used for the requisite adjustments to data processing
within the group.
</P>
<P>
However, the Euro introduction will also cut the company's
currency exposure by about 30 percent, thus largely eliminating
performance risks from unforeseeable exchange-rate fluctuation,
Gentz said.
</P>
<P>
"This would yield greater security for corporate planning, in
turn considerably enhancing the operating conditions for the
individual business units," Gentz added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
