<HEADLINE> Largest Cargo Ship Transits Suez Canal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The world' largest cargo ship, a
91,000-ton Danish ship, passeed through the Suez Canal today
coming from Spain en route to Singapore carrying 4,742 containers.
</P>
<P>
The ship is 347 meters long, 42.80 meters wide and has a
draught of 12.75 meters, according to the Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Suez Canal Authority (SCA) Ahmed Ali FAdel said
it was the first time that this ship transited the waterway.
</P>
<P>
"The policy of the SCA is to attract huge ships of all types to
use the Canal," he said.
</P>
<P>
The ship paid 358,000 U.S. dollars in transit fees.
</P>
<P>
The 195 kilometers Suez Canal is the longest waterway in the
world without locks. As Egypt's third largest foreign currency
earner, it garnered 2.1 billion dollars in 1995 but the revenues
declined to 1.88 billion dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
The Suez canal, the first canal directly linking the
Mediterranean Sea to the Red Sea, was opened for international
navigation on November 17, 1879 and Egypt nationalized it on 26
July, 1956. 
</P>
</TEXT>
