<HEADLINE> Tanzania Seeks to Curb Periodic Fires on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania is designing
strategic plans to curb periodic fire outbreaks on the
Kilimanjaro mountain, the highest in Africa.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by Chairman of the National Environmental
Management Council (NEMC) Reginald Mengi during his five-hour
tour to fire-ravaged moor land area standing at an altitude of
about 3,000 meters above sea level.
</P>
<P>
Mengi was accompanied by three officials with the council and
journalists during his tour on Monday to the mountain, in
northern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
However, the official declined to give details of the proposed
plans, saying that NEMC will present the proposal to the
vice-president, Omar Ali Juma for endorsement before they were
made public for implementation.
</P>
<P>
It was earlier reported that the fire which erupted on
September 3 has allegedly destroyed over 10,000 hectares of
forest. But NEMC officials and reporters found that the figures
were exaggerated, which created unnecessary fear among tourists
who had planned to scale the 5,895-meter-high mountain.
</P>
<P>
Mengi called on Kilimanjaro National Park Management to
compile correct data on fire disasters so that true information
can be disseminated to the people and visitors to the country.
</P>
<P>
He also urged journalists to assess and verify the size of
forest areas alleged to have been ravaged by fire instead of
being spoon fed by the park management personnel whose data and
figures were sometimes conflicting and misleading.
</P>
<P>
Some reports said 500 to 5,000 hectares were affected by the
inferno.
</P>
<P>
The NEMC chairman also lashed out at some villagers in the
mountain who assumed a nonchalant attitude toward the fire. He
said that since fire outbreaks pose as a common enemy, local
villagers, like other people, were bound to extinguish it to
demonstrate patriotism.
</P>
<P>
They are not expected to stay aloof, hoping the government to
do the job, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Joins in 19 Peace-keeping Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has contributed forces to
19 peace-keeping operations throughout the world since its
independence in 1960, a National War College provost said today.
</P>
<P>
The country also provided 12 force/field commanders and chief
military observers during the period, said retired Maj.-Gen.
Charles Ndiomu, provost of the college's center for peace,
research and conflict resolution.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, of the nine distinguished African generals ever
entrusted with the overall command of U.N.-peace keeping
operations, four were supplied by Nigeria," Ndiomu said at a
lecture in the capital Abuja, quoted by the News Agency of
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
According to military sources, Nigerian peace keepers have
been sent on missions in a number of countries and regions,
including the former Yugoslavia, Angola, Western Sahara,
Cambodia, the Gulf, Liberia and Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Describing Nigeria as a credible peace-keeping nation, the
provost called on the international community to devise
appropriate strategies to cope with the resurgent of ethnic,
social, cultural and linguistic conflicts which threaten
international peace.
</P>
<P>
Other dangers that need to be addressed included disparities,
intolerance, human rights violation, the proliferation of weapons
and other forces of disintegration, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ndiomu also urged the international community to carry out
serious, in-depth, systematic and sustained studies in the area
of conflict and peace so as to work out the strategies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
