<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Rocky Road Ahead for Renewed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Breaking the nearly
seven-month long deadlock in the peace process, Israeli and
Palestinian negotiators finally sat down today to resume the
negotiations on implementing the signed peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
The resumption of the peace talks was the result of the
intensive mediation efforts launched by U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and special peace envoy Dennis Ross who
presided over the meeting Monday night between Israeli Foreign
Minister David Levy and deputy head of Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen).
</P>
<P>
Levy and Mazen decided to reactivate the nine joint committees
created after the signing of the Hebron redeployment deal last
January on implementing the Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
Both sides stressed their commitments to the signed accords,
and expressed their desire to advance the peace process through
conducting negotiations and the common fight against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The seven-month deadlock, caused by Israel's start of building
the controversial Har Homa settlement in Arab East Jerusalem
last March, has led to increased tension between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
And the July 30 twin suicide bombings in the Mahane Yehuda
market and September 4 triple bombings in the Ben Yehuda
pedestrian mall in central Jerusalem, both claimed by the
militant Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas), dealt further blows
to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In its tough reaction, Israel imposed draconian sanctions
against the Palestinians, including a total closure of the
self-rule areas, a ban on the entry of Palestinian workers into
Israel and a freeze on transferring tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
The PNA denounced the sanctions as a form of collective
punishment against the whole Palestinian people, thus demanding
an end to the sanctions before resuming security cooperation with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
But Israel insisted that the lifting of sanctions and
resumption of peace talks should be conditional on the PNA's real
actions to resume security cooperation with Israel and to crack
down on Hamas and other militant groups.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of the Ben Yehuda bombings, the Israeli government
decided to freeze the Oslo process by halting handing over more
land to the PNA.
</P>
<P>
To avoid further deteriorating of the situation, the
U.S. government intervened by trying to bridge the differences
between the two sides. In early August, Ross traveled to the
region to pave the way for the first Middle East trip by Albright
in early September.
</P>
<P>
Although Albright's visit failed to achieve a breakthrough in
breaking the peace deadlock, it did help ease the tension by
hearing complaints from both sides.
</P>
<P>
Her visit also led to the series of top-level meetings between
senior Israeli and Palestinian officials in the United States,
during which the two sides agreed in principle to return to the
negotiating table.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Rocky Road Ahead for Renewed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Top on the agenda of the
renewed negotiations are the implementation of the rest of the
Interim Agreement, primarily the opening of safe passages between
the West Bank and Gaza Strip, the accelerated construction of
Gaza seaport and Gaza airport, and Israel's implementation of
further troop redeployments in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Despite the renewal of peace talks, outstanding obstacles
remain unresolved between Israel and the PNA in pushing forward
the peace process so to proceed onto the final status talks.
</P>
<P>
Technically, it is expected to take time for the two sides to
overcome the dispute on security arrangements in the Gaza airport
and seaport. Israel hopes to execute security control over the
two ports in order to prevent the smuggling of weapons that could
threaten its security.
</P>
<P>
As for the implementation of further Israeli troop
redeployments, huge gap still exists between the two sides over
the scope of pullouts. Israel only agrees to relinquish about 40
percent of the West Bank after completing all the pullouts, but
the PNA hopes to gain over 80 percent of land on which it wants
to create a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Under the Note for Record attached to the Hebron agreement,
Israel should have completed the first of the three-stage
pullouts by March 7, but it has been delayed due to the PNA's
refusal to accept the 9 percent scope set unilaterally by
Israel. And the second phase of redeployment has also been
indefinitely postponed due to the freeze of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
However, the leading obstacle blocking the peace process will
be the lack of trust and confidence, which have been destroyed by
the bloodshed in late September last year and by Israel's
continued settlement activities.
</P>
<P>
Israel's decision in September last year to open an
archaeological tunnel near the Al-Aqsa mosque, the third holiest
Islamic shrine in Jerusalem, led to days of bloody clashs between
the Palestinians and the Israeli forces, in which over 70 were
killed and hundreds of others wounded.
</P>
<P>
To rebuild the trust and confidence, both sides should
refrain from making further unilateral steps in preempting the
negotiations in the final status talks. But, unfortunately, there
has been no signs so far from the Israeli government on showing
flexibility to make compromise on the issue of expanding
settlements.
</P>
<P>
Albright has already urged Israel to create a favorable
environment to rebuild mutual trust and confidence by agreeing to
accept the time-out of its settlement activities. In the days to
come, the definition of so-called time-out will dominate the
talks.
</P>
<P>
In view of the political reality within the hardline Likud
government, which consists of some hardcore rightists insisting
on Israel's claim to all the occupied land, it will be very
difficult for Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to make
compromise on the settlement issues.
</P>
<P>
And the common worry amounts to be that the Israeli
intransigency, combined with prolonged lack of progress in future
peace talks, will likely lead to another circle of tension and
violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
