<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Frees 9 Jordanian Detainees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Nine out of 23 Jordanians detained
in Israeli jails have been released to put Jordanian-Israeli
relations back on normal track, said a senior Jordanian official.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 14 Jordanian prisoners were expected to be set
free soon thanks to Jordanian King Hussein's mediation, said
Minister of State for Information Affairs Samir Mutawe' here today
after a cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
Israel now has pledged to Jordan to abide by all the provisions
in the peace treaty it signed with the kingdom, he added.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral relations went strained since Israeli spies'
attack on Khaled Mashaal, head of the Islamic Resistance Movement
(Hamas) political bureau, here on September 25.
</P>
<P>
Hussein raised the demand for Israel to release Hamas leader
Shiekh Ahmad Yassin, as well as Jordanian and Palestinian
detainees during a public gathering a week ago.
</P>
<P>
Israel then met the demand after Jordan promised to set free
the two Israeli agents caught in attacking Mashaal.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Deputy Prime Minister for Services and Minister of
Administrative Development Abdullah Ensour Monday (October 6)
admitted that the releases were the results of "a good bargain"
between Jordan and Israel, which benefited all the sides concerned
including Hamas.
</P>
<P>
Hamas was established in 1987 to fight against Israel`s
occupation of Palestine. The movement has conducted a series of
anti-Israeli attacks since 1994, with many of its leading figures
staying in Amman.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994 and is
now one of the only two Arab countries that conceived peace with
the Jewish state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Calls for NATO Expansion Ratification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright today launched the administration's campaign
for Senate ratification of the expansion of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
"A larger NATO will make America safer, NATO stronger and
Europe more peaceful and united. That is the strategic rationale,"
Albright told the Senate Foreign Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
At a summit in Madrid in July, the 16-member alliance decided
to invite former Warsaw Pact members Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic to join.
</P>
<P>
Albright was the first administration official to testify
before the Foreign Relations Committee, chaired by Jesse Helms, a
conservative Republican. The full Senate is expected to vote on
ratification next spring.
</P>
<P>
She told the committee that NATO was enlarged because it would
"expand the area in Europe where wars simply do not happen;" it
would make NATO stronger by adding new countries that would help
accomplish alliance goals; and it gave central European countries
an incentive for resolving age-old disputes between them.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Albright dismissed fears that NATO expansion would
create a new threat from Russia, which has strongly opposed the
expansion.
</P>
<P>
"The dire predictions about the end of the world if NATO
enlarged are not coming true," she said.
</P>
<P>
Members of the committee expressed support for the principle of
expansion, but urged the administration to strike a deal first
with Europeans on burden-sharing over the costs of the expansion.
</P>
<P>
Helms told Albright that ratification of the expansion plan
"could very well succeed or fail" on whether the Europeans are
persuaded to pay their fair share.
</P>
<P>
Albright replied, "As secretary of state, I will insist that
our old allies share this burden fairly. That is what NATO is all
about."
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the U.S. government estimated that the total
cost of the expansion will be some 35 billion U.S. dollars over 10
years, but said the U.S. share would be only about 2 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Albright said the U.S. and its allies were working to produce a
common estimate of costs by December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
