<HEADLINE> Egypt Tells Israel: Murder Attempt Harms Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa today described Israel's failed attempt on the life of a
Hamas leader last month as "dangerous and detrimental" to the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters, Moussa warned that the chain of violence
will have its evil repercussions on the region's security.
</P>
<P>
"The ongoing state of affairs will ultimately undermine the
Mideast peace process," he said.
</P>
<P>
Any government that respects itself can not accept what has
happened, the Egyptian top diplomat noted, adding that "The tone
of threats will never be useful and will never intimidate anybody."
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the attack by two Israeli agents on Khaled
Meshaal, political chief of Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas),
in Amman on September 25.
</P>
<P>
Hamas was established in 1987 to fight against Israel`s
occupation of Palestine. Most Hamas political bureau members live
in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Jordan are the only Arab countries that have
diplomatic ties with the Jewish state. 
</P>
