<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tory Leader Pledges to Rebuild Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Conservative leader
William Hague has pledged to rebuild his party, urging party
members to learn from past mistakes and to embrace change.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the party's first annual conference since its
disastrous general election defeat in May, He said he was "under
no illusion" about the task ahead.
</P>
<P>
In his interview with the Times Monday, Hague confessed that
the Tories seemed "divided, self-obsessed, arrogant and
conceited."
</P>
<P>
However, his proposed internal party reform received the
backing of over 80 percent of party members polling 143,299 votes.
Those voting against him totaled 34,092.
</P>
<P>
The Tory leader said he saw the endorsements of his leadership
by the party as "the beginning of a challenge to be met."
</P>
<P>
And he said he would do everything "in his power" to rebuild
the party. "This is the week when we get off our knees and stand
tall again," he added.
</P>
<P>
Hague also called on the party: "We must now turn our energies
to the future." 
</P>
</TEXT>
