<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-07 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qatar: Economic Conference Not to Be Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Qatar today ruled out the
possibility of postponing the Middle East and North Africa
Economic Conference, saying it will convene as scheduled on
November 16 to 18.
</P>
<P>
Qatar today began sending invitations to foreign states and
international organizations, Fuaz bin Ahamad al Atuiya, spokesman
of the Qatari Foreign Ministry was quoted by the Qatari news
agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said media reports asserting the suspense of the conference
were "not correct."
</P>
<P>
The Qatari foreign ministry made the statement after the
Qatari news agency reported last Saturday that "Qatar has the
capacity of postponing the conference."
</P>
<P>
Syria, Lebanon, the Palestinian National Authority, Saudi
Arabia and the UAE have decided to boycott the conference in
protest against the deadlock in the Arab-Israeli peace process
while most of other Arab states adopt a wait-and-see stand.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League made a decision in September to leave Arab
countries free on their participation in the conference, the
fourth since it was launched in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Israel have announced their participation in the
conference. Qatar said last week that it will invite Israel's
Foreign Minister David Levy instead of Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Doha said last Wednesday that the conference could be
downgraded from a summit to a conference at a ministerial level
because the atmosphere is not "appropriate" for inviting higher
level officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
