<HEADLINE> Mozambique Trains 11,074 Pharmacists in 20 years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique has trained 11,074
pharmacists in the past 20 years, Ivo Garrido, head of the Higher
Institute of Mozambique's Science and Technology, said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening session of the first International
Conference of Portuguese-speaking Pharmacists here, Garrido said
these pharmacists are of primary and middle levels.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that there are only five senior pharmacists in
the country which has a population of about 17 million.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the meeting, Mozambican Deputy Minister of Health
Abdul Razak said parliament will approve the new draft pharmacy
act which encourages the private sector to participate in making
medicines and the liberalization of their imports.
</P>
<P>
Private participation will promote investment in drugs
production and their sales, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the conference, Renato Ronda, President of the
Association of Pharmacists of Portuguese-Speaking Countries, said
it "has committed to the moral and professional obligation of
improving the health system of Portuguese-speaking countries."
</P>
<P>
Personnel training, the restoration of the circulation
channels of the medicines, their storages and imports are high on
the agenda of the four-day conference.
</P>
<P>
Some 150 people from Portugal, Mozambique and Cape Verde are
attending the meeting while other members including Brazil,
Angola, Guinea-Bissau and Sao Tome and Principe are not
represented. 
</P>
</TEXT>
