<HEADLINE> Indian PM Specifies Coop Areas With S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister
Inder Kumar Gujral today specified fields of cooperation with
South Africa, the South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Time has come for the two countries to build "a rapidly
growing super structure of cooperation," Gujral told South
African parliament in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
He said India can profit from South Africa's skills and
technology in the fields of mining and infrastructure
development.
</P>
<P>
India, in turn, can be of special help in the development of
small scale industries, the housing sector, human resource
development, employment-generation programs and in science and
technology as well.
</P>
<P>
A second area of great importance, he said, was the
strengthening of joint endeavors in regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We see South Africa as a bridgehead into the markets of
southern Africa and we can play the same role for your country as
a spring board into South Asia and beyond," Gujral told South
African parliamentarians.
</P>
<P>
He called on both countries to play a definitive role in
strengthening the Indian Ocean rim cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The two countries head the Indian Ocean Rim Alliance for
Regional Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He also called for greater cooperation between the two
countries in world forums such as the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM)
and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
He said the NAM is still necessary to address problems facing
the developing world.
</P>
<P>
On United Nations reform, Gujral said both countries have an
important responsibility to help reform the global organization,
especially its Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, the two leaders presided over the signing of
three agreements in geology and mining resources, tourism, and
science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Indo-South African relations saw rapid development in recent
years. The two countries agreed to establish a "strategic
partnership" in the Red Fort Declaration signed by Mandela and
then Indian prime minister Deve Gowda during Mandela's visit to
India in March this year.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade grew to over 600 million U.S. Dollars last
year from some 80 million U.S. Dollars in 1993. Gujral predicted
that the figure could reach one billion by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Gujral's visit to South Africa, which is the first by an
Indian prime minister, was given special significance because
this year is also the 50th anniversary of India's independence
from Britain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
