<HEADLINE> Liberia Impounds Secret Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Liberian policemen
are keeping guard on an airfield near the capital Monrovia a day
after a South African plane made an unscheduled landing there.
</P>
<P>
Three South Africans and four Sierra Leoneans who arrived by
the plane were also being investigated by a joint team of the
Liberian security force and officers from the west African
peace-keeping force known as ECOMOG, the British Broadcasting
Corporation reported today.
</P>
<P>
Liberian Justice Minister Peter Bona Chana said this afternoon
that the aircraft had been impounded because of the secrecy about
its arrival in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
According to him, several items found aboard the plane have
been extended over to ECOMOG, which is in overall charge of
Liberia's security.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ECOMOG Commander Major-General Victor Malu was
quoted as saying that his military intelligence officers were
handling the matter.
</P>
<P>
The plane arrived on Sunday on route of Sierra Leone from
Conakry, capital of Guinea, with the three South Africans and
four Sierra Leoneans on board.
</P>
<P>
The Sierra Leoneans have been identified as members of the
Kamajors, a group of traditional hunters fighting against the
military junta for the restoration of President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah ousted in the May 25 coup.
</P>
<P>
The justice minister said the police were enforcing the
seizure of the aircraft because "it is related to the security of
the state of Liberia". 
</P>
