<HEADLINE> US-Syrian Talks in New York Make Little Progress: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States' ambassador
to Lebanon said today that the talks between U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright and her Syrian counterpart Faruk Shareh
in New York made little progress.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz,
U.S. Ambassador Richard Jones told reporters here that the gap
between Albright and Shareh remained so wide that they couldn't
reach any agreement to revive the Syrian-Israeli and
Lebanese-Israeli tracks of peace process.
</P>
<P>
But, he said the United States will make efforts to relaunch
the peace negotiations between Israel and the Palestinian
National Authority through U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross who is
now in Israel for peacemaking.
</P>
<P>
Jones stressed that efforts being made on the
Israeli-Palestinian track do not mean that other tracks are
neglected.
</P>
<P>
The talks between Shareh and Albright in New York was the
result of the latter's first tour of the Middle East region
including Syria last month.
</P>
<P>
Syrian-Israeli peace talks broke down last year after a spate
of suicide bombings hit Jerusalem. Syria refused to return to the
negotiating table, accusing Israel of not honoring the commitment
of the former Israeli government to return the occupied Golan
heights.
</P>
<P>
Syria has been insisting that the Syrian-Israeli negotiations
should resume from where they halted in May, 1996, but the
Israeli govenrment said that the talks should start anew without
any precondition.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting between Boueiz and Jones focused on a U.S. aid
program to train Lebanese soldiers and civilians to remove thousands
of mines planted in Lebanon. 
</P>
