<HEADLINE> Clashes Between Somali Fisherman, Foreign Vessels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The anarchy and civil strife
in Somalia are not confined to the mainland of the country alone,
but also occur along the beach lines off Somali Coast which
stretches more than 3,333 km, the longest in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Seven Somalis were wounded last week when fighting broke out
between local fishermen and four foreign fishing vessels off Ego
Beach, about 340 km north of the capital Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Mohamud Ali Arrale, head of a local fishing company based at
Ego Beach, complained that the four foreign ships flying the
flags of Greece, South Korea, Pakistan and Italy, looted quite a
number of fishing nets with lobsters valued at more than 12,000
U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Arrale, who contacted the VHF radios, accused the foreign
vessels of looting and fishing in Somalia's waters illegally.
</P>
<P>
Reports said about a dozen Somalis with two small fishing
boats and equipped with assault rifles attacked the four vessels
off the coast of Ego Beach.
</P>
<P>
In the fighting that ensued, the foreign vessels used heavy
machine guns which forced the local fishermen to retreat to the
mainland, while the big ships went out of sight, Arrale added.
</P>
<P>
Hassan Eid Omar, an engineer and also one of the fishermen,
said this is the third time in two months that their nets were
looted by big vessels.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the fishermen are now working with heavy
machine guns on their boats and he threatened they will destroy
every foreign fishing vessel they see in their area of operation.
</P>
<P>
"We're going to fight the illegal fishing and looting to the
last drop of our blood," Omar swore.
</P>
<P>
A similar net looting business involving foreign vessels
occurred at Adale district beach four months ago. Mohamud Alasow
Kurdi, deputy district commissioner, said the foreign vessels
have looted all the nets laid by the local fishermen. Two of the
local fishermen were wounded while fighting with these foreign
fishing vessels at the district, about 100 km east of Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Abdi Wade, interior secretary of Ali Mahdi Mohamed's
faction, said the case of the illegal fishing and looting by the
foreign vessels will be thoroughly investigated and that measures
will be taken against them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
