<HEADLINE> Netanyahu to Be Questioned Over Spy Attack Affair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu is due to be summoned for questioning by a
three-member committee over the failed attack on Hamas leader
Khaled Mashaal in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that the committee, appointed by the
Israeli government to investigate the Mashaal affair, began its
work today and no deadline was set for the investigation.
</P>
<P>
Local press and politicians have pointed out that Netanyahu is
the person empowered to issue the final order for such attacks.
</P>
<P>
The committee comprises former legal advisor of the Defense
Ministry Yosef Ciechanover, ex-Mossad (Israeli secret service)
director Nahum Admoni and ex-police inspector-general Rafi Peled.
</P>
<P>
Two Mossad agents holding forged Canadian passports launched
the attack on Mashaal on September 25. But they were arrested on
the scene.
</P>
<P>
To rescue the two agents, Israel released Hamas founder Sheikh
Ahmed Yassin and allowed him to return to the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The radio report quoted diplomatic sources in Jerusalem as
saying that as soon as Netanyahu knew the assassination was
botched, he decided to send Mossad chief Danny Yatom for a meeting
with Jordan's King Hussein and give Jordanians drug to neutralize
the poison injected into Mashaal's ear in order to save the life
of the two secret agents.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has promised Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan that
Israel will do its most to ensure that such attack will not occur
again, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
He also phoned Hussein Monday night and noted that the two
countries have acted "cautiously and responsibly" in handling the
Mashaal affair. Netanyahu said that the damage must be repaired to
ensure the Israeli-Jordanian relations to remain in all spheres.
</P>
<P>
The sources also confirmed that Hamas did offer a possible
ceasefire to Israel, but the intelligence information reached
Netanyahu only after the attack on Mashaal.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai indicated
today that he had not been involved in making any major decisions
concerning with the Mossad operation in Jordan. He said that he
was closely involved in the affair only after it happened, and he
just made efforts to minimize the damage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
