Norwegian prime minister today pledged more health fund to
African countries if she was elected as director-general of the
World Health Organization (WHO).
</P>
<P>
She made the remarks to the press here after concluding her
two-day visit in Angola.
</P>
<P>
At present, she said, African countries account for only 17
percent of WHO's fund. She promised to mobilize the
organization's fund to help promote the health cause on the
African continent.
</P>
<P>
The former premier believes that it takes close cooperation
for the whole world to overcome poverty and improve education and
health systems so as to achieve sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
To accomplish this, she added, international organizations
must work together through various channels.
</P>
<P>
According to Brundtland, her current African tour also
includes South Africa, Botswana, Tanzania and Egypt. She will
meet with leaders of these countries and visit health
institutions to get to know health situations in African
countries and people's general demands in this regard so as to
make her election more favorable to African countries.
</P>
<P>
Brundtland arrived here on Monday in a bid to lobby support
for her campaign for the post of WHO's director-general. 
