rebel faction, describing the Fashuda accord signed late September
as "a real contribution to peace."
</P>
<P>
Bashir and Lam Akol discussed the situation after the signing
of the peace agreement between the government and Lam Akol group
in Fashuda, southern Sudanese upper Nile province, Secretary
General of the Supreme Peace Council Mohamed Amin Al Khalifa told
newsmen.
</P>
<P>
On negotiations between the Khartoum government and John
Garang, leader of the largest rebel faction Sudan People's
Liberation Army (SPLA), which are scheduled to take place in
Nairobi on October 28, Al Khalifa expressed the government's
readiness and interest in reaching an agreement.
</P>
<P>
Al Khalifa called upon Garang to be serious this time so that
the Sudanese people might establish unity and peace throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government had signed peace accords with two
thirds of the principal rebel groups in southern Sudan. It signed
the Khartoum peace agreement last April with six southern rebel
groups.
</P>
<P>
However, the Garang-led SPLA still refuses to make compromise
with the government. Garang is adamantly demanding the
establishment of an independent state despite all the peace
efforts made by the government.
</P>
<P>
Sudan's civil war has claimed lives of over a million since
1983 when the southern rebels took up arms for greater autonomy
from the Islamic north for the Christian and animist south.
</P>
