<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt said it plans to inject 88 billion U.S. dollars
over 20 years in agricultural, industrial and tourism projects as
well as in development of new towns in the country's southern
desert region, the latest issue of Middle East Times weekly
reported.
</P>
<P>
The government has outlined the major components of a
development plan for southern Egypt, said Public Works Minister
Mahmoud Abdel Halim Abu Zeid.
</P>
<P>
"The government will finance more than 25 percent of the
investments and the rest will be funded by the private sector,"
the minister added.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The total volume of U.S. aid to Egypt for the 1997
U.S. fiscal year reached 809 million U.S. dollars, with the
signing of new grant agreements with Cairo in September, the
Middle East Times reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreements, Egypt will receive 143.5 million dollars
in U.S. grants to develop its commodities market, small and
medium-size businesses, water and waste-water schemes and
family-planning program, the English weekly quoted U.S. officials
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 U.S. fiscal year ended on September 30.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Direct foreign investments in Egypt are expected to
soar to 1.5 billion U.S. dollars by the end of 1997, the latest
issue of Middle East Times reported.
</P>
<P>
Economy Minister Youssef Boutros Ghali said last week that
direct investment stood at 900 million dollars in 1996, up from
432 million the year before.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the increase to the government's privatization
policy, which came into force in 1996.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's tax revenues will show a shortfall in the
whole year of 1997 over the targeted revenues set by the Israeli
Treasury for this year if the revenues continue to be collected at
the current rate, the Israeli Treasury announced today.
</P>
<P>
The tax revenues totaled 81.3 billion shekels (about 23.2
billion U.S. dollars) in the first three quarters of this year,
representing a mere 1.7 percent increase over the same period in
1996.
</P>
<P>
But if revenues continue to be collected at the current rate,
they will show an 4.5 billion shekels (about 1.3 billion dollars)
shortfall in 1997 on the targeted revenue, which was set at 113.4
billion shekels (32.4 billion dollars) by the Treasury.
</P>
<P>
Tsipi Galyam, head of Israeli State Revenue Administration,
said that in a bid to increase the revenues, he has called for
wide-spread reform of the taxation system, including widening the
tax base and a substantial reduction in tax exemptions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
