<HEADLINE> Ericsson to Increase Production in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Swedish company Ericsson
plans to increase its turnover in Russia from this year's some 350
million U.S. dollars to 850 million dollars in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"Our forecasts show that we will have a turnover of 850
million U.S. dollars in the year 2000, but I wouldn't be surprised
if we reach 1 billion dollars," said Yngve Redling, CEO of
Ericsson's Russian subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
Ericsson is expected to have a turnover of some 350 million
dollars in Russia this year.
</P>
<P>
Ericsson has decided to build a second factory in Russia this
year. Ericsson's first factory in Russia, an AXE exchange
production plant, is scheduled to start operation on January 1,
1998.
</P>
<P>
The company also decided to increase the number of its offices
in Russia from eight to 15 next year, its workforce from 350 to
600, and its joint ventures from five to eight.
</P>
<P>
Ericsson now takes about 50 percent of the mobile telephone
market in Russia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
