<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Moves on Supplementary Pension Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 8 (Xinhua) -- In a drive toward the single
market, the European Commission today adopted a proposal for
union-wide legislation on safeguarding the supplementary pension
rights of employees.
</P>
<P>
The proposed council directive fills a significant gap in
existing European Union (EU) legislation by preserving acquired
rights, guaranteeing cross-border payments and making it possible
for workers temporarily posted by their employer to work in
another EU member country to remain affiliated to the
supplementary pension scheme in the country where they were
previously working.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, people who move from one job to another within
the 15-nation union face losing all or part of their supplementary
pension rights. This represents a significant obstacle to labor
mobility.
</P>
<P>
The proposal is deemed as the first step to removing the
obstacle to free movement that is one of the two basics on which
the single market is to be forged.
</P>
<P>
The other basic is the free movement of goods.
</P>
<P>
State pensions have already been covered by the EU free
movement legislation. But for many workers, supplementary pensions
are becoming more significant in financial terms and their
importance is still growing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
