<HEADLINE> China, Egypt Agree to More Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 8 (Xinhua) -- China and Egypt today signed a
letter of intent for boosting economic and technological ties and
increasing mutual investment.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed to encourage joint ventures,
especially in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
China promised to subsidize its firms that are willing to
invest in Egypt, while Egypt pledged a favorable climate for them.
</P>
<P>
The letter of intent was signed by Chinese Ambassador to Cairo
Yang Fuchang and Chairman of Egypt's General organization for
Investment and Free Zones Ibrahim Fawzi.
</P>
<P>
"The signing of the document indicates that both the Chinese
and Egyptian sides have a strong desire to promote cooperation
between them in the economic and technological fields," Yang said
following the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The climate of good relationship between the two countries
dates back to the 1950s and the economic ties have increased
remarkably.
</P>
<P>
China and Egypt signed an agreement for the prevention of
double taxation between them in August. A free trade zone in Suez
is under construction with Chinese technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
Two-way trade volume for last year was 400 million
U.S. dollars. China's main exports are light industrial products,
electrical items, minerals and metals, while Egypt's exports to
China are mainly crude and oil products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
