<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Strict on College Diploma Granting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese students who fail to
pass the national college entrance exam must be cautious when
answering enrollment advertisements for various nongovernment
colleges and universities, according to an official from the State
Education Commission (SEC).
</P>
<P>
Some nongovernment colleges avoid responding to queries
concerning whether or not they grant official diplomas to
graduates, said the official.
</P>
<P>
Only 20 nongovernment colleges and universities nationwide have
received SEC authorization to grant diplomas recognized by the
government.
</P>
<P>
Students attending other nongovernment colleges and
universities are required to pass a national exam for
self-learners in order to receive an official diploma.
</P>
<P>
Students who have attended nongovernment colleges and
universities recognized for providing high-quality education can
take a provincial exam authorized by the state government. Those
passing said exam will receive an official college education
certificate.
</P>
<P>
People holding official diplomas find it much easier to find
employment.
</P>
<P>
No changes have made in college enrollment policy, according to
the official. However, beginning autumn semester this year, all
Chinese colleges and universities will charge tuition fees
to cover between 10-20 percent of college education expenses
formerly subsidized by the government.
</P>
<P>
All colleges and universities will enroll freshmen in
accordance with the state plan, and only students enrolled under
said plan will receive official college education certificates upon
graduation.
</P>
<P>
The official stressed that students enrolled outside of the
state plan will not receive official diplomas after graduation.
Nongovernmental colleges and universities supplement formal
college education by enabling people who fail the entrance exam to
receive a college education.
</P>
<P>
However, some nongovernmental colleges and universities promise
students they will receive an official diploma in order to enroll
more students and increase revenues. The official warned students
and parents to exercise caution which receiving promises of this
nature.
</P>
<P>
A list of colleges and universities authorized to grant
official diplomas will published in "China Education Daily" each
year prior to the enrollment period.
</P>
<P>
Chinese colleges and universities grant graduates legitimate
diplomas printed by a confidential professional unit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Demilitarization Only Solution to Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides has reiterated that only demilitarization can bring a
"visible" solution to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark Tuesday in Washington on the sidelines of
the 13th Hellenic-American Conference, Cyprus News Agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The present status quo on the island, which is divided into
Turkish Cypriots-controlled north and Greek Cypriots-dominated
south, is not acceptable as a solution, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that "The island must be demilitarized by having the
Turkish forces withdrawn" from the northern island.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island became divided after Turkish troops took over the northern
third of the island in the wake of a short-lived pro-Athens
coup. Turkey maintains about 30,000 troops there.
</P>
<P>
The president stressed that the Cyprus problem is not a problem
between the two communities on the island but a problem between
Turkey and Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The obstacle to progress on the Cyprus issue is not Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash but Turkey, he said, adding that
"That is where all the attention should be directed and our
efforts should be made to bring Turkey to realize that the
solution to the Cyprus problem is a must."
</P>
<P>
President Clerides made the proposal for demilitarization
three years ago, which promises disbanding the Cypriot National
Guard and handing over its weapons and equipment to the
U.N. Peace-keeping Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP).
</P>
<P>
In return, the proposal calls for withdrawal of the Turkish
troops from the island and disbanding of the Turkish Cypriot
armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Clerides repeated the proposal during his direct talks with
Denktash in Montreaux, Switzerland, in August, but was rejected
by the Turkish side.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the view that the only country that can help
solve the Cyprus problem is the United States. "We hope that the
U.S. will play a role in the upcoming negotiations," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Establishes Postal Financial Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 8 (Xinhua) -- China's postal financial network
currently consists of over 2,300 commercial outlets in 50 cities,
according to an official from the Ministry of Posts and
Telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that plans call for the network to be
further expanded to 500 cities with more than 10,000 service
branches by the end of the century. He said the network will
primarily specialize in nationwide deposit and remittance services.
</P>
<P>
The ministry established the postal financial network, or the
"Green Card Project" in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Beijing and Shanghai, as well as Dalian in northeast China's
Liaoning Province, were in the first group of pilot cities
introducing the network.
</P>
<P>
Beijing, the Chinese capital, has since establish links with
167 affiliated networks, and has installed 87 Automatic Teller
Machines, according to Xu Xueming, director of the Beijing Bureau
of Postal Savings and Remittance Services.
</P>
<P>
Recent statistics show that trade volume for Beijing's postal
financial network reached 81 million yuan (about 10 million US
dollars) worth between June and August this year
</P>
<P>
Xu noted that Beijing has established a computerized banking
system linked to 33 major cities, with plans calling for the
service to be expanded to an additional 10 cities, including
Guilin and Chongqing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
