<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reports Show D.C. Police Department in Chaos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Reports say police department
of the District of Columbia, the United States, loses evidence,
wastes money, makes poor personnel decisions and loads its
unmanned property warehouse with guns and drugs.
</P>
<P>
The findings were detailed by consulting firm Booz-Allen and
Hamilton Inc., in several reports obtained by The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
The reports found appalling conditions in the police evidence
warehouse.
</P>
<P>
Much of the evidence found in police storage is more than 10
years old and often misclassified, according to the reports. The
evidence warehouse and drug labs also are piled high with guns and
narcotics that are "vulnerable to direct attack," one report said.
</P>
<P>
The sites are guarded only by motion sensors and alarms, the
report said. Medical evidence stored in the area also is
mishandled, routinely spoiling in the heat and creating hazardous
conditions.
</P>
<P>
The post quoted unidentified police officials as saying the
department cannot find seven percent of the 1,594 motor vehicles
assigned to it and that many felony cases are dismissed because
evidence is lost in computer crashes.
</P>
<P>
Poor personnel practices in D.C. police department was also
cited. Senior officers often were assigned to low-level posts in
the mail room, file room and photo gallery, one report said.
</P>
<P>
Police Chief Larry Soulsby, who has been chief for two years,
did not dispute the findings. "We are changing every unit," he
told the Post. "These are things that have been wrong for 20
years. They didn't occur overnight." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
