<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Gives Green Light to Production of Eurofighter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The German government today finally
gave the long-delayed approval for funding the Eurofighter
project, clearing a major outstanding hurdle to production of a
21st-century warplane for Britain, Germany, Italy and Spain.
</P>
<P>
Under a decision made today by the German cabinet, the German
air force Luftwaffe would be able to order 180 Eurofighter jets at
total costs of about 23 billion marks (13 billion
U.S. dollars). It would be the biggest and most expensive military
project for Germany in the post-war era.
</P>
<P>
Although okeyed by the government, Germany's eventual
participation in the project still depends on the final approval
next month by the parliament's lower house, the Bundestag, where
it could meet rejections mainly from the opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
The Eurofighter project have been controversial in Germany at a
time when Bonn is struggling to curb public spending in order to
meet the fiscal requirements for qualifying for the planned single
European currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
Development of Eurofighter prototypes has already cost German
taxpayers 7 billion marks (4 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, Daimler-Benz Aerospace AG, the German contractor of
the four-nation group that will build the modern jet, argued that
the jobs and technological payoff of the project were
indispensable to the future of the company and a German place in a
European aircraft industry.
</P>
<P>
German Defence Mininster Volker Ruehe today also said that
after nine years of planning and development, the Eurofighter had
reached a technical stage at which preparations for mass
production could begin.
</P>
<P>
Britain, Italy and Spain have already approve the project, with
London planning to buy 232 Eurofighters, Rome 121 and Madrid 87.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the Eurofighter project is estimated at about
75 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inter-Korean Air Control Agreement Initialed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) and South Korea today initialed an air control
agreement, paving the way to open an inter-Korean air route for
commercial flights.
</P>
<P>
The arrangement came at the third round of inter-Korean
aviation meeting held in Bangkok, Thailand, under the auspices of
the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO), said the
Ministry of Construction and Transportation.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed Tuesday to use a direct telephone line via
Panmunjom as the main control communication means and AsiaSat and
InterSat as a secondary means for linking South Korea's Taegu and
the DPRK's Pyongyang Flight Information Regions (FIR).
</P>
<P>
The two sides on the Korea Peninsula have banned each other's
national flag carriers from passing through their territorial air
space since the peninsula was divided in 1945.
</P>
<P>
A nation controlling the FIR provides airplanes flying inside
the zone with flight information. If an accident takes place in
the zone, the nation is responsible for search, rescue and
investigation.
</P>
<P>
Designed to facilitate flights for international civil
airliners through the FIR of the two sides, the agreement will
take effect on February 28 next year, according to ministry
officials.
</P>
<P>
When the Pyongyang FIR is used, South Korean planes flying
between Seoul and Vladivostok or American cities could reduce
flying hours by 20 to 47 minutes, while saving about 14 million
U.S. dollars worth of fuel one year.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the DPRK would make a profit of some 2 million dollars
in air control fees a year, said the official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0086 </DOCNO>
