<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Troops Restore Combat Capability: Officer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Ali Al-Mumen, Kuwaiti chief
of staff of the armed forces, has asserted that Kuwaiti troops
have restored combat capabilities and are ready to repulse any
aggression.
</P>
<P>
According to local Al-Rai Al-Aam newspaper today, Al-Mumen said
in an interview that the armed forces have been successfully
rebuilt to face any eventuality six years after Kuwait's liberation.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait had about 20,000 troops before the Iraqi invasion in
1990. However, the military was crushed by advancing Iraqi forces
and during their ensuing seven-month occupation.
</P>
<P>
Al-Mumen said that in addition Kuwait has formed the reserves
which could join the armed forces within 24 hours to deal with any
emergency. But he did not mention the size of the reserves.
</P>
<P>
He said the Kuwaiti-Iraqi borders are calm recently. "But this
does not mean that we should stop our military preparations. We
should stay vigilant as long as there is a conflict," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He maintained the necessity of diversifying stockpiles of arms
and conducting intensive training of the forces.
</P>
<P>
"After liberation, we began a new phase of intensive training,
field and moralistic preparedness," he stressed, adding that the
national air, ground and naval forces are trained to keep a high
state of readiness.
</P>
<P>
After the Gulf War, Kuwait signed defense cooperation treaties
with the United States, Britain, France and Russia to purchase
nearly 130 billion U.S. dollars worth of advanced military
equipment within 10 years. 
</P>
