<HEADLINE> Chinese Government Maps Out Autumn Grain Purchase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 8 (Xinhua) -- As autumn harvest is
approaching, the State Council, China's highest governing body,
issued a circular today, urging localities to earnestly carry out
government grain purchase policies so as to protect farmers'
interests.
</P>
<P>
The circular demands the purchase prices for autumn grain
remain at the same level of last year, and grains outside the
state-set quotas should be purchased open-endedly and at the
government protective prices. Any violations should be severely
punished.
</P>
<P>
Illegal dealers who buy grains from farmers at lower prices but
sell them to the state at higher prices must be timely cracked
down, the circular says.
</P>
<P>
To stem speculation, the circular calls for stricter grain
market management while banning any private firms or individuals
from involved in grain purchase. It states that "only state-run
grain enterprises have the right to directly buy grains from
farmers."
</P>
<P>
It cautions state grain shops to sell grains in accordance with
government policies, and "should not lower sale prices", the
violators should be responsible for the losses themselves.
</P>
<P>
The circular also urges local grain department to make good
preparations for the upcoming autumn purchase, including revamping
and building more granaries and barns, installing more stoving
equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
