<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is to launch a National
Health Insurance Scheme (NHIS) next Wednesday, Health Minister
Ihechukwu Madubuike announced Tuesday in Abuja.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the kick-off of the NHIS is in recognition
of the government's social responsibility of providing
accessible, affordable and equitable health care services.
</P>
<P>
Many Nigerian states have shown interests to NHIS, but he said
only eight states and the Federal Capital Territory of Abuja have
been selected to pilot the scheme.
</P>
<P>
The eight states are Kano, Kaduna, Plateau, Lagos, Ogun,
Enugu, Rivers and Borno.
</P>
<P>
Establishment of the NHIS has been discussed in Nigeria for
decades, but all the previous attempts to launch it have failed.
</P>
<P>
With the costs of medical care soaring in recent times, common
Nigerians have denied access to essential medical services. There
have been many reports of patients being denied treatment for
failing to pay huge deposits.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the minister said, providing free medical
care to civil servants has become an unbearable burden to the
government. 
