<HEADLINE> Interconnect Agreement Ends Telecom. Monopoly in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 8 (xinhua) -- The monopoly of the Nigerian
Telecommunications Limited (NITEL) came to an end Tuesday in
Lagos, with the signing of an interconnect agreement between it
and Multi-Links, a private telephone operator.
</P>
<P>
The agreement would allow subscribers of both firms to reach
the networks of the other, thus adding 10,000 lines to the
existing 700,000 lines in the national telephone networks, press
report said.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government deregulated the telecommunications
sector five years ago by Decree 75 of 1992, but Multi-links is
the first private firm to enter an interconnect agreement with
NITEL, thus formally ending the latter's monopoly over the
sector.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony, NITEL's managing director,
Buba Bajoga remarked that the agreement "has put to rest the
public anxiety over private partcipation in the nation's
telecommunications market".
</P>
<P>
Multi-Links chairman, Alhaji Lema Jubril thanked NITEL for its
co-operation and pledged to take advantage of the agreement to
provide quality services to complement NITEL's effort. 
</P>
