<HEADLINE> Nigeria Considers Exchange Rates Merger in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government is
considering a merger of the country's dual exchange rates in the
1998 budget, "This Day" newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Although no decision has been taken, an official from the
Ministry of Finance was quoted as saying that "hopefully we will
deal with the issue (dual exchange rate) once and for all in the
1998 budget".
</P>
<P>
The official exchange rate now stands at 22 Naira to one U.S.
Dollar, while the rate at the autonomous foreign exchange market
is about 82 Naira to one Dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government has been under pressure to merge the
two rates. It was widely expected to do so in the 1997 budget,
but it didn't take the step at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the dual exchange rate regime is now
considered by the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) as the sole grey area in Nigeria's economic health.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria might have to bow to the pressure if it is to benefit
from the various debt relief programs monitored by the World Bank
and the IMF, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The institutions also insist that dual exchange rate prevents
the optional allocation of resources and hinders transparency and
accountability, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
