<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Ready to Help Stop Algeria's Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia has expressed
readiness to help stop Algeria's continued violence, Kuwaiti News
Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
While meeting with the visiting Algerian President Liamine
Zeroual on Tuesday in Jeddah, Saudi King Fahd said that his
country is willing to make efforts to help contain the situation
in Algeria, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Zeroual started on the day his first visit to the Gulf kingdom
since taking office in 1995 to hold talks with Fahd on bilateral
and regional issues, the report said.
</P>
<P>
He briefed Fahd on the escalating violence in Algeria and his
government's efforts to end the bloody killings.
</P>
<P>
More than 60,000 people have been killed in Algeria since 1992
when the Islamic Salvation Front began an insurgency after it was
robbed of by the military-backed government a parliamentary
election victory.
</P>
<P>
In recent months, militants began to commit group massacres in
villages and towns, each of which left dozens of civilians dead.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, Fahd and Zeroual discussed means of
promoting bilateral cooperation in political and economic fields,
according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
On the Middle East peace process, the two sides stressed the
necessity to resume negotiations on all tracks in accordance with
the United Nations resolutions and the land-for-peace principle.
</P>
<P>
On the Gulf issues, the two sides stressed that regional peace
and stability could not be maintained until Iraq has fully
implemented all the U.N. Security Council resolutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
