<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democracy, Freedom Valued in HK: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Although livelihood-related
topics occupied much space in his maiden policy address, it
doesn't necessarily mean that democracy and freedom are neglected
in Hong Kong, Chief Executive of the Special Administrative Region
 (SAR) Tung Chee Hwa said here today.
</P>
<P>
Instead, the whole society has attached much importance to
democracy and freedom, Tung told a press conference after
delivering his policy address at the Provisional Legislative
Council this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Since July 1, the way of life of the Hong Kong people has not
changed and freedom, including the freedom of the press, is well
preserved, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Concerning the SAR's political development, the Basic Law sets
out a 10-year timetable for the elections of the chief executive
and the legislative council and the arrangement meets the needs of
Hong Kong society, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"We'll take time to move forward," he continued, adding that
all should remember that the long-term objective of the HKSAR, as
laid down in the mini-constitution of the SAR, is to have a chief
executive and a legislature elected by universal suffrage.
</P>
<P>
The 10-year period is reasonable, since many countries in the
world spent years and years in moving from indirect election to
direct election to universal suffrage, he stated.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the chief executive stressed, "the important
thing is to make sure this government is accountable to the
people, the rule of law continues to be strong and freedom
prevails, and we will make sure all these continue in Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
Responding to a number of questions on housing, Tung said there
is "no magic solution" to the problem. "What the government can
do is offer more land and housing units."
</P>
<P>
He voiced confidence that the three main housing targets laid
down in his policy address will be achieved -- to build at least
85,000 flats a year, to achieve a home ownership rate of 70
percent in 10 years and to reduce the average waiting time for
public rental housing to three years.
</P>
<P>
Turning to why the policy address was so lengthy and touched so
many topics, Tung said that as the first policy address of the
SAR, it signified a new era of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
On the one hand, it defined the SAR's direction of future
development with a macro perspective; on the other, it addressed
the issues of current concern for Hong Kong people, he said. It
took Tung two hours and 10 minutes to read the 42-page address.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the capital expenditure of 88 billion HK dollars
(11.3 billion U.S. dollars) over the next five financial years,
Tung said the money, covering long-term investment in fields such
as infrastructure and schools, will anchor Hong Kong into the next
century.
</P>
<P>
The number itself, viewed as a lucky one by Chinese, is not a
design, he said, arousing a burst of laughter.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 questions were asked in the crowded 45-minute
press conference, covering old-age welfare, labor, high-tech
development, culture and relations between Hong Kong and China's
interior. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
