<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to Tighten Curbs on Internet-Based Drug Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government will clamp
down on imports and sales of unauthorized foreign drugs by agents
trading on the Internet, a local press report said today.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese Health Ministry is planning to monitor the
Internet more closely in order to track down agents behind the
illegal trade, ministry officials were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Such unauthorized medicines traded over the Internet include
rejuvenating drugs for insomnia and appetite suppressant, both of
which are produced in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also will warn Internet users in Japan of possible
adverse consequences of buying unauthorized drugs.
</P>
<P>
Japan's move came as the World Health Organization (WHO) called
for countermeasures against increasing illegal drug trading over
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The WHO adopted a resolution at its general meeting in May
appealing for tougher control of rampant international drug
trading.
</P>
<P>
Japanese doctors and patients are still entitled to directly
import some unauthorized drugs abroad for special personal needs,
an exception which makes it difficult to control drug trading on
the Internet, government officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Indonesia Tries to Boost Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government today
made a series of decisions to tackle the currency, monetary and
other economic issues emanating from the recent volatility and
depreciation of the country's currency and boost people's
confidence in the economy.
</P>
<P>
At a limited cabinet meeting held at the Presidential Palace,
President Soeharto decided that all relevant ministers and
institutions are to safeguard stocks of essential goods and strive
to maintain price stability.
</P>
<P>
The president ordered all the institutions to implement
earnestly the decision made in September to postpone and review
some government and private projects.
</P>
<P>
In order to deal with all possibilities, including external
volatility, Soeharto said, Indonesia will continue to pursue
prudent economic management and undertake those structural
adjustments needed to enhance the efficiency and competitiveness
of the country's economy in the face of global competition.
</P>
<P>
To accelerate economic activities and help medium-sized and
small businesses as well as cooperatives, he said, the government
will continue to cautiously ease liquidity as warranted by the
economic situation.
</P>
<P>
According to the decisions reached at the meeting, the
Indonesian government is considering seeking long-term loans from
world bodies, including the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to
strengthen its financial sector.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto also said the government will continue to implement
consistently the free foreign exchange system.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's rupiah has dropped by 50 percent against the U.S.
dollar and the stock prices plunged by more than 20 percent since
the beginning of this year following offshore speculative attacks
on the currency and a rush by local companies to hedge their
foreign borrowings.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah, which stood at 2,400 to a dollar in early July,
is now 3,600 to 3,700 to the greenback.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the depreciation of the rupiah, many sectors in
the country, especially small enterprises, banks and the tourism
sector, have been facing a very difficult time.
</P>
<P>
Some economists said Indonesia's economy is going through its
toughest time since the oil crisis in the 1980s.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0106 </DOCNO>
