<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Inflation Hits 5.37 Percent in 9 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's inflation in the
period from January to September 1997 was 5.37 percent, narrowing
the chance of keeping this year's inflation at last year's level.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bureau of Statistics (BPS) said here today the
figure is higher than the cumulative inflation in the
corresponding period
of last year, when inflation was recorded at 4.94 percent.
</P>
<P>
In September 1997 alone, inflation was 1.29 percent while in
the same period of last year, the country saw a deflation of 0.04
percent.
</P>
<P>
The BPS said the increase in the price index of food,
multifarious goods, services and housing pushed up September's
inflation.
</P>
<P>
It said the price index of food rose by 1.91 percent,
multifarious goods and services 1.29 percent and housing 0.82
percent.
</P>
<P>
Official sources attributed the higher inflation to the
long-running dry season and the monetary crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
The prolonged drought has caused a rice production decrease and
forest fires in many areas while the Indonesian rupiah has
depreciated by about 50 percent following the monetary turmoil in
the Southeast Asian region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
