<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian PM Warns Duma Against No-confidence Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Victor
Chernomyrdin today urged Russia's Communist-led parliament to back
down from a threatened no-confidence vote in his government over
its economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
In his speech to parliament's lower house, or the State Duma,
Chernomyrdin tried to win support for key economic reforms that
include new tax laws and the 1998 budget.
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced the country and the Russian people do not need
the vote or new elections," Chernomyrdin said.
</P>
<P>
The Communists, the biggest parliamentary group holding 140 of
the 450 seats in the Duma, said today it will seek a no-confidence
vote next week.
</P>
<P>
They said the 1998 draft budget, to be debated in the Duma on
Thursday, sets too high targets and includes more spending in some
areas.
</P>
<P>
If the no-confidence vote passes, it will be non-binding. But
if a second no-confidence motion were passed within three months,
President Boris Yeltsin would be forced to either dismiss his
cabinet or disband the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has made it clear he might be forced to dissolve the
Duma and call a new parliamentary election.
</P>
<P>
But to avert a showdown, Yeltsin told Chernomyrdin to persuade
the Duma into approving the draft 1998 budget -- an important part
of its economic program.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said the economy has rebounded after six years of
decline, and a political confrontation now could lead to another
setback.
</P>
<P>
"We need to start responsible dialogue. The government is ready
for this," Chernomyrdin said while outlining Russia's economic
performance.
</P>
<P>
He said the gross domestic product (GDP), the broadest measure
of economic health, had risen 0.2 percent in the first nine months
of the year against the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Russian production rose 1.5 percent in January-September
1997, after falling 4.5 percent in the first nine months of 1996
over the same period in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in Russian in the first half of 1997
totalled 7 billion U.S. dollars, 230 percent up against the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin also predicted a good grain harvest this year at
84-85 million metric tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
