<HEADLINE> Tanzania Manages to Tackle Power Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 8 (Xinhua) -- There will be no power
blackout in Tanzania as the government is taking measures to
tackle the present power crisis resulted from long-time drought.
</P>
<P>
This was assured by Minister for Energy and Minerals Abdallah
Kigoda when talking to industrialists and other businessmen here
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Kigoda said that the government is aware of the seriousness of the
problem to the country's economy and is doing all it can to alleviate
it.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government will exempt from paying duty to
industrialists who will import generators for power supply to
their industries.
</P>
<P>
He listed short-term measures in addressing the power crisis
such as leasing of power budgets to prospective investors,
importing power from neighboring Zambia for which the two
countries signed a memorandum last June.
</P>
<P>
Kigoda said that a long-term measure is the Songo Songo
gas-to-electricity project whose contract will be signed at the
end of next month or early December.
</P>
<P>
Power rationing began last month in the whole country of
Tanzania. Preliminary forecast says that due to erratic power
supply, industrial production is likely to fall by more than 15
percent in the 1997/98 financial year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
