<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 06:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Netanyahu, Arafat Meet Secretly to Boost Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 8 (Xinhua) -- In a sign of further thawing
in ties between Israel and the Palestinian National Authority (PNA),
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and PNA leader Yasser
Arafat held a secret meeting this morning to give a boost to the
just-renewed peace process.
</P>
<P>
This was the first meeting between the two leaders since the
peace process grounded to a standstill in March when Israel began
building the controversial Har Homa settlement in East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that Netanyahu and Arafat met for three
hours early this morning at the Erez checkpoint between
Israel and the Gaza Strip. The meeting was arranged by visiting United
States special peace envoy Dennis Ross, who has just presided
over the ceremony Monday night of resuming the peace talks after
a nearly seven-month deadlock.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders first talked privately in a "good atmosphere"
and then were joined by Ross, Netanyahu's attorney Yitzhak
Molcho, PNA deputy head Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen) and Palestinian
Council Speaker Ahmed Qureia (Abu Ala).
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, which was kept away from the press, Netanyahu
and Arafat reportedly agreed to work together to fight terrorism
and advance the peace process. They agreed to renew the security
talks between Israeli and Palestinian intelligence services on
fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu told Arafat that Israel would not relax its
continuous fight against terror and he expected the PNA to adopt
the same policy.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the meeting, Ross hailed the summit as a "new
beginning" between the leaders and for the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said the two leaders agreed that, in addition to the
negotiations that have been resumed on the interim committees,
they should see all these kinds of resumption and contacts on
all levels between the two sides and the two leaders be held at
a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
"We are obviously trying to make headway on the interim
issues, we also clearly want to try to find the best possible
way to move forward on the broad questions to allow the whole
process back on track," Ross said, noting that major differences
between the two sides remained.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that the negotiations between Israeli
Foreign Minister David Levy and Mazen scheduled for next week in
Washington had been postponed to the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
The Netanyahu-Arafat summit indicated a further thawing in
the strained relations between the two sides and the two leaders
since early this year because of Israel's settlement activities
and the recent wave of terror attacks in Jerusalem launched by
the militant Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas).
</P>
<P>
The meeting, held just after both sides agreed Monday to
reactivate the nine joint committees on implementing the rest of
the Interim Agreement, was the first positive sign showing that
the derailed peace process was finally back on track.
</P>
<P>
But tough tasks are awaiting for negotiators from both sides
as they will try to solve the differences over the interim
issues, including the opening of the safe passages, construction
of the Gaza airport and seaport and release of Palestinian
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
In addition, huge gap still exists between the sides over
deciding the scope of the three-phase Israeli troop redeployments
in the West Bank, which should be completed by mid-1998. The
first and second stages of pullouts, scheduled to be finished by
September 7, have been indefinitely delayed by the scope
dispute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Africa Plans Regional Women's Organization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Plans are underway to
establish a regional apex body for a women's organization in East
Africa, according to a news dispatch from Arusha, northern
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Magaga Alot, a senior member of the East
African Commission at a gender workshop in Arusha on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Presenting a paper "Role of Women in the East African
Cooperation (EAC)", Alot said when full fledged, the evisaged
women's regional organization will among others, serve as a
center for articulation, harmonization, and promoting of women's
rights and roles within the framework of the EAC and regional
integration.
</P>
<P>
Alot said that the apex body will also address issues such as
women's participation in decision-making at all levels and access
to social resources, including education, employment, health and
population services.
</P>
<P>
He stressed, "Women account for roughly 50 percent of the
combined population of the three (EAC) member states of Kenya,
Uganda and Tanzania" and the EAC cannot ignore the plight or
contribution of half of its human resource while pursuing
regional integration and development.
</P>
<P>
Alot noted that what women need and deserve is nothing more
and nothing less than the affirmation of their equal rights and
opportunities under the law and in the society at large. 
</P>
</TEXT>
