<HEADLINE> Kenya's Stock Market Set for Record-Breaking Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Nairobi Stock Exchange (NSE) is
set for a record-breaking year in spite of the prevailing
political and economic uncertainty in the country, the East
African Standard reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted NSE Chairman Jimnah Mbaru as saying Tuesday
that at the end of last month, turnover in the equities secondary
market was more than 5 billion Kenyan Shillings (about 80 million
U.S. Dollars), 28 percent higher than the 1996 turnover.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the turnover should easily surpass the 94
million Dollars mark by the end of the year, compared with 61.2
million Dollars in 1996 which was itself an 18 percent increase
over the 1995 levels.
</P>
<P>
The NSE has attracted a net foreign investment of 21.4 million
Dollars since the beginning of this year despite the stand-off
between the Kenyan government and the International Monetary Fund
in July.
</P>
<P>
According to local press reports, as one of the leading stock
exchanges in Africa, the NSE must have benefited from the pool of
investment funds set aside for African markets.
</P>
<P>
Mbaru was addressing brokers, bankers, investors and the
business fraternity when he launched the Nairobi Stock Exchange
Facts and Figures 1997 Handbook in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of reliable, timely, relevant and
accurate information for the stock market, which "has become a
powerful tool transcending geographical boundaries and moving
financial markets worldwide."
</P>
<P>
The handbook is edited and published by Economic Intelligence
Ltd. which is specialized in the provision of strategic research
and financial information service to local and international
investors, corporate executives and business analysts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
