<HEADLINE> Desertification Threatens Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- One third of Uganda experiences
frequent and prolonged drought and is threatened by
desertification, reported the local daily, The New Vision today.
</P>
<P>
Israel Kibirige Sebunya, State Minister for Agriculture was
quoted as saying the most threatened areas of the country are
those in what is known as "cattle corridor" stretching from
Karamoja, in the northeast, through Teso in the east and
Nakasongola in the central part to Rakai and Nyabushozi in the
southwest.
</P>
<P>
Sebunya pointed out that drought, commonly experienced in many
parts of Uganda in recent years is largely responsible for the
recent famine in the country.
</P>
<P>
On the causes of land degradation which leads to desert-like
conditions, the minister said that in addition to drought,
overgrazing of cattle, deforestation and poor farming practices
are major land degrading factors in the dry lands of Uganda.
</P>
<P>
These factors have been intensified by poverty, a factor which
compels people to over exploit the land resource in order to
survive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
