<P>
LUSAKA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Zambia will amend its constitution
early next year to remove the two term limit clause and allow
President Frederick Chiluba to hold a third tenure of office, claimed
opposition United National Independence Party (UNIP).
</P>
<P>
At a weekly news briefing here Tuesday, Bweendo Mulengele,
UNIP secretary for publicity and information, claimed without
proof that the ruling Movement for Multi-party Democracy (MMD)
wants the two term presidential limit constitutional clause
changed to allow President Chiluba a longer period, the Post
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The relevant bill will be submitted before parliament by
January 1998 after an MMD convention that will have Chiluba as
sole candidate, said Mulengele.
</P>
<P>
Under the current constitution, the president's tenure of
office is limited to two five-year terms. Incumbent President
Chiluba came to power in 1991 and was reelected last year.
</P>
<P>
Mulengele's allegations were denied by David Mpamba,
government spokesman and minister of information and broadcasting
</P>
<P>
He said there is no such plan to amend the constitution which
the MMD itself formulated.
</P>
<P>
Richard Sakala, Chiluba's public relations and press
assistant, said that the president is working toward improving
democracy in Zambia and therefore cannot do such a thing.
</P>
<P>
The president never thought of that and the MMD has never
planned to change the constitution to stand for the third term,
said Sakala, adding Chiluba will leave the office at the end of
the day and allow a logical succession. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
