<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 08:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriots Invited to Join Talks with EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Foreign Minister
Ioanuis Kasoulides has reaffirmed that his government invites
Turkish Cypriots to take part in the coming accession negotiations
with the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
According to local reports today, Kasoulides said at a press
conference after talks with EU foreign ministers in Luxembourg
Tuesday that "the invitation still stands, despite the fact that
the first reaction of the Turkish Cypriot leader was negative."
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government has asked the Turkish Cypriots to join
the Cyprus delegation which is expected to negotiate the country's
entry to the EU early next year.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, in his last round of
direct talks with Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides, refused to
negotiate a settlement for the protracted Cyprus problem unless
the EU freezes the accession talks with the Cyprus government.
</P>
<P>
The two communities on the east Mediterranean island has long
been embroiled in a bitter vendetta, with Greece and Turkey
standing by each of them. In 1974 Turkey sent troops to take over
the northern third of the island in the wake of a failed coup by
the Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The island has since remained divided and in 1983 the Turkish
Cypriots declared a breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern
Cyprus" recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkey was reportedly infuriated by the EU decision to go ahead
with accession talks with Cyprus while it is left behind.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot foreign minister assured his EU counterparts that
Cyprus could act as a bridge between the EU and the eastern
Mediterranean region as soon as it becomes an EU member.
</P>
<P>
He said Cyprus is ready to help in Albania's economic
reconstruction and wishes to contribute to EU's involvement toward
this goal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
