<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Employment Bill Criticized in Zambian Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The employment amendment bill
came up in parliament here Tuesday amid criticism from
independent and opposition parliament members that its enactment
will condemn workers to shanty-town dwellers.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the bill, Labor and Social Security Minister Peter
Machungwa said that the government wants to make employees less
dependent on their employers by making it not mandatory for
employers to accommodate their workers.
</P>
<P>
He said the bill also seeks to reduce government intervention
into the worker-employer relations because this is deterrent to
economic growth and makes it difficult to attract investment into
Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Some independent and opposition members said that the issue of
accommodation is a crucial one and should not be left to
collective bargaining because bulk of employees have no unions to
represent them.
</P>
<P>
Independent member Crispin Sibetta said it is surprising that
the government which mostly comprised former labor leaders is now
in the process of passing a law to make even the provision of
advances of salaries for workers negotiable.
</P>
<P>
Labor and social security deputy minister Syamuchaye
Madyenkuku said no reasonable employer with the capacity will
deny his employees houses, housing allowance or advances of
salary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
