<HEADLINE> Four Coffee Dealers Licensed in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Coffee Board of Kenya (CBK)
has issued licenses to four new coffee auctioneers as a further
step in the liberalization of the industry, the East African
Standard reported today.
</P>
<P>
Coffee auctions have in the past been the preserve of Kenya
Coffee Auctions, a subsidiary of the CBK, but now the company
will have to fight for business among the new entrants.
</P>
<P>
At a ceremony held here Tuesday to introduce the new entrants,
CBK public relations manager Paul Kivila said that CBK was
committed to total liberalization of the coffee industry.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the coffee farmers in the country were now
free to choose who will be auctioning their products among the
new companies.
</P>
<P>
Kenya resumed its weekly coffee export auctions Tuesday after
canceling the September 30 auction due to supply shortage.
</P>
<P>
The next auction will be held on October 21 and the auctions
are expected to remain once-weekly probably in early November
when the supplies of new coffee crop begin coming in. 
</P>
</TEXT>
