<HEADLINE> Drought-Hit Zambian Farmers Urged to Reduce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lusaka, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Zambia National Farmers Union
(ZNFU) has urged farmers to reduce the size of their cattle herds
in view of the impending drought.
</P>
<P>
ZNFU president Ajay Vashee said in Ndola, northern Zambia,
Tuesday that it is important for the farmers especially in the
drought prone areas to reduce the size of their herds to avoid
losing cattle during the drought.
</P>
<P>
"The farmers should start culling now. It is important to
lessen the pressure on the pasture because of the drought that is
impending," he was quoted by Times of Zambia as saying.
</P>
<P>
Vashee also warned poultry and pig farmers that the prices of
stock feed might rise because of the expected shortage of maize.
</P>
<P>
"Stock feed largely depends on maize and because of the
situation at hand, the prices will go up," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said ZNFU will embark on a country-wide tour to educate
farmers on the impending drought and there is currently a
shortage of drought resistant seeds.
</P>
<P>
However, he said farmers in the northern region of the country
could plant maize because the prices will be good if the
government does not manipulate the market.
</P>
<P>
"If the government does not interfere or manipulate the market
the prices will be reasonable. For this reason only maize will be
profitable and farmers in good rainfall areas should plant
maize," the farmer union leader said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
