<HEADLINE> UN Trains African Planners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Third Africa Training
Course on Local and Regional Development and Planning started
here today with 32 participants from 17 African countries.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is organized by the U.N. Center for Regional
Development and the U.N. Development Program and funded by the
Japanese government.
</P>
<P>
The course, serving as a forum for discussions on the nature
and causes of social and economic crises in Africa, will seek
ways of revitalizing local economies and strengthening their
sustainable institutional capacity against crises.
</P>
<P>
It also provides a forum for African professionals, scholars
and administrators to share their experiences and exchange
informations.
</P>
<P>
Among the participants are those from Cameroon, Equatorial
Guinea, Guinea, Sao-Tome, Senegal and Sudan. The course will end
on November 19.
</P>
<P>
The first international training course targeting mainly
Africa started here in 1995. 
