<HEADLINE> S. African Farmers to Plant Maize to Limit El </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 8 (Xinhua) -- South African farmers are
working out the best time to plant maize in a bid to limit the
potentially devastating effects of the El Nino weather
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
Local farmers agreed to choose maize as a better crop to
withstand drought which might result from the coming El Nino
phenomenon, but they had different views over the best time for
planting maize.
</P>
<P>
There are two schools of thought on the best planting time.
Some believe that it is better to plant early and cash in on the
present high moisture levels of the soil, but others feel it is
best to delay planting and adopt a wait-and-see attitude.
</P>
<P>
National Maize Producers' Organization Director Kit le Clus
said early this week that farmers could not delay decisions any
longer.
</P>
<P>
He said it was best to plant hardy, drought-resistant
cultivars, choose lands with a high soil moisture content, and
possibly bring planting times forward.
</P>
<P>
Scientists and weather analysts have kept warning that the
current season could see one of the worst droughts in memory in
South Africa as a result of the potent El Nino phenomenon
developing in the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
South Africa suffered the worst drought caused by the El Nino
phenomenon in 1982-83, which caused damages of about 2.1 billion
U.S. Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Gains From Smooth U.S.-Indonesia Ties: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Australia can only gain from
using its "unique" position to help smooth relations between
Indonesia and the United States, Australian Prime Minister John
Howard said today.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister confirmed a previously undisclosed agreement
for senior Australian and American officials to discuss Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The officials held their first meeting in Washington on
September 16, the Australian Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
The aim is to use Australia's special knowledge of its neighbor
Indonesia to help heal a rift between Jakarta and Washington, the
news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Australia was particularly worried that Washington's sharpened
criticism of human rights abuses in Indonesia was damaging
relations between two of its most important friends.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is listed as one of the four most important nations
to Australia in a white paper on foreign affairs and trade
released in August by the Australian government.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to journalists today during his tour of the island
state of Tasmania, Howard confirmed that he raised the issue with
President Bill Clinton in Washington in June.
</P>
<P>
He had told President Clinton that Australia had a "particular
knowledge of this region and particular knowledge of circumstances
inside Indonesia," which meant that Australia could play a role in
better explaining to the Americans what was happening in
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Howard said President Clinton responded favorably and, as a
result, working parties of officials from both sides had got
together.
</P>
<P>
He said there would be benefits to Australia in being seen to
be a country with close links with nations like Indonesia and
being able to use them to help the United States gain a better
understanding.
</P>
<P>
"And it's in our interests that the Americans remain involved
in the region, in our interests that Americans properly understand
the dynamics of the Indonesian polity and the dynamics of the
Indonesian economy," Howard said.
</P>
<P>
As 60 percent of Australia's exports go to Asia, Australia is
keen to see stable and smooth political and economic development
in the region, particularly Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Australian economists have already been worrying about the
negative impact on Australia's economy and job creation caused by
the financial crisis going on in Southeast Asia, which they fear
would affect the region's imports from Australia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
