<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Aviation Expo Opens in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The 7th Aviation Expo/China '97,
the country's oldest and most authoritative aviation exhibition,
opened here today, concurrently with the running of the Airport
Exhibition Expo/China '97.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Wu Bangguo cut the ribbon to open the event.
</P>
<P>
The expo has attracted more than 260 exhibitors from 24
countries and regions, and will include exhibits by many of the
world's top aircraft and spare parts producers and major airlines,
including US-based Boeing and Airbus from Europe, as well as
other aviation leaders from Germany, Britain, France, Japan,
Russia, and China.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition provides a venue for the companies to show their
state-of-the-art aviation and airport equipment for both military
and civilian use.
</P>
<P>
The expo will also feature various aviation technology
seminars, financial business discussions, and a series of
commercial negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Exhibits will cover over 10,000 sq.m. in the China
International Exhibition Center.
</P>
<P>
Organizers predicted that the four-day expo will attract over
100,000 visitors.
</P>
<P>
The expo is jointly sponsored by the Civil Aviation
Administration of China (CAAC), Aviation Industries of China,
China National Aero-Technology Import and Export Corporation,
China Aviation Supplies Import and Export Corporation, the China
Council for the Promotion of International Trade, and the Hong
Kong-based China Promotions Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Sponsors noted that the biennial aviation expo is the fourth
largest one of its kind in the world, and the largest of its kind
in China. The scale of the event has remained constant since the
first expo held in 1984.
</P>
<P>
China's civil aviation sector continues to enjoy rapid and
sustained development, with a roughly 20 percent annual increase
over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
The figure is expected to remain at around 12 percent through
the end of the century, with China requiring the addition of some
250 airliners, according to estimates by Chen Guangyi,
director-general of CAAC. The country's 43 airline companies had a
total fleet of 800 aircraft at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
International aviation companies are eyeing the booming Chinese
market which is a major reason why the current Beijing Aviation
Expo is such a huge attraction, said Chen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
