<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Policy for 1998 Australian Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- New and less fluffy balls will
be used and an overall roof policy will be in effect at next
year's Australian Open, according to the tournament's organizers
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Big serve-and-volley players complained last year that the
balls used in the first grand slam event of the season were too
soft and slow and were causing wrist and elbow injuries.
</P>
<P>
The decision of using new balls was made to avoid high
percentage of rejection as last year.
</P>
<P>
The roof policy also sparked controversy this year. A heatwave
hit the tournament and the organizers had to shut the roof on the
center court.
</P>
<P>
Tournament director Paul McNamee said at a news conference that
they would have an overall heat policy next year including when to
shut the roof and when to suspend play on outside courts.
</P>
<P>
Prize money next year will be lifted by five percent to 7.2
million U.S. dollars, organisers said.
</P>
<P>
Current singles champions Pete Sampras and Martina Hingis have
both confirmed they will defend their titles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
