<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Considers Seeking IMF Long-Term Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia is considering seeking
long-term loans from world bodies, including the International
Monetary Fund (IMF), to strengthen its financial sector, a senior
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The move is aimed at strengthening the country's foreign
exchange reserves, Finance Minister Mar'ie Muhammad said following
a limited cabinet meeting on economy.
</P>
<P>
Mar'ie said that the government has been closely consulting the
World Bank and the IMF about the matter and that the two bodies
will send their teams to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
He did not specify the amount and terms of the long-term loans
the country will obtain from the two bodies.
</P>
<P>
"We are considering obtaining long-term loans from
international financial institutions and these loans will merely
function as standby loans," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bank Indonesia (central bank) Governor Soedradjad
Djiwandono said the country's foreign exchange reserves stand at
21.4 billion U.S. dollars, consisting of 20.532 billion dollars
kept in the central bank and 900 million dollars in private banks,
which are enough to finance the import of non-oil/gas commodities
in the next five months.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the country also has standby loans worth nearly 2
billion dollars which can be disbursed any time, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mar'ie also said the government will list all private loans to
know their exact amounts and their maturity dates.
</P>
<P>
On the monetary crisis in the country, particularly the
rupiah's depreciation by about 50 percent since the beginning of
this year, both Mar'ie and Soedradjad considered the devaluation
an exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
"Although the rupiah has been floated, we will continue to try
to prevent further depreciation (of the rupiah against the U.S.
dollar)," Mar'ie said.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah is now 3,600 to 3,700 to a dollar.
</P>
<P>
Mar'ie and Soedradjad reiterated the government's determination
to maintain the free foreign exchange system.  
</P>
</TEXT>
