<HEADLINE> Visiting British FM Calls on Pak Prime Minster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif today assured the visiting British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook of his commitment and contribution to the advancement of the
relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Sharif also briefed Cook, who called on the prime minister
earlier in the day, on the sweeping and revolutionary measures
adopted by his government to deregulate, liberalize and privatize
the economy, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister expressed his hope that these measures would
encourage and stimulate the interest of British investors to
invest in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Cook said the new Labor government of
Britain is anxious to further strengthen its ties with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Cook praised the Pakistani government's economic policies and
described the future outlook of British investment in Pakistan as
good.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sharif briefed Cook on the Indo-Pakistan dialogue,
particularly on the Kashmir issue, and the latest situation in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister stressed that he has approached the dialogue
with sincerity of purpose.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that India would reciprocate and especially realize
the importance of the Kashmir issue to the improvement of
relations between Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
The continued tensions in the Subcontinent, whose root cause is
Kashmir, has been hindering the progress of nearly 1 billion
people, Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
Underlining the need for a just and fair solution to the
Kashmir issue, Cook said Britain would be happy to help in any
manner that is possible to facilitate the resolution of the
problem.
</P>
<P>
Sharif and Cook also exchanged views on the forthcoming
Commonwealth Summit to be held this month, according to the
sources.  
</P>
