<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Leader Optimistic About Ties with Motherland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) Tung Chee Hwa today
expressed optimism about the future relations between the SAR and
the motherland, noting that they share the same fundamental
interests.
</P>
<P>
Presenting his first Policy Address before the Provisional
Legislative Council this afternoon, Tung said Hong Kong has
"incomparable advantages" including that Hong Kong is "the
southern gateway to China" and that Hong Kong's "future economy
will also be strongly supported by the rapid development" in the
motherland.
</P>
<P>
"In terms of the overall economic development of the SAR and
the motherland, prospects are bright," he said. "Strengthening
economic cooperation with nearby provinces and cities is of
particular importance to the future development of Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
He said: "Hong Kong's reunification with China under the 'one
country, two systems' concept requires us to appreciate and accept
one practical and profound truth: Hong Kong's prosperity and
stability are closely linked with those of the mainland." Also, he
continued, Hong Kong and the motherland "share the same
fundamental interests."
</P>
<P>
It also is the starting point for the SAR government when
formulating policies for the SAR's relationship with the
motherland and strategies for the SAR's long-term development, the
Chief Executive said.
</P>
<P>
In recent decades, he said, Hong Kong and the motherland have
established broader and closer relationship in many areas. With
Hong Kong's return to the motherland, the relationship between
Hong Kong and the motherland should flourish comprehensively in
all fields such as the economy, finance, trade, transport,
culture, education, science and technology, tourism and sports,
he added.
</P>
<P>
"The policy of reform and opening up in the motherland has
given new energy to Hong Kong's economic development," Tung noted.
"In our daily lives, we enjoy the benefits of our country's rapid
economic development."
</P>
<P>
According to the Chief Executive, building on past cooperation,
the SAR government and the relevant inland areas' authorities have
agreed that a Hong Kong and Motherland Major Infrastructure
Projects Coordinating Committee be re-established to handle a
number of cross-boundary infrastructure projects between Hong Kong
and Guangdong province.
</P>
<P>
It will conduct in-depth studies on specific projects, such as
the Western Corridor, the Zhuhai Lingdingyang Bridge, the Tonggu
Channel, air traffic control coordination between the new airport
and the Pearl River Delta, the Lok Ma Chau and Huanggang boundary
crossings and others, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, he said, "in order to strengthen comprehensively
Hong Kong's regional cooperation with Guangdong province, the SAR
government and the Guangdong provincial government, in conjunction
with relevant central government departments, will establish a
high-level framework to study and coordinate major issues such as
infrastructure, environmental regulation, supply of non-staple
foods, water supply, social welfare, business investment and the
speeding up of the flow of passengers, traffic and freight across
the border, enabling cooperation between Hong Kong and Guangdong
province to rise to new heights."
</P>
<P>
"Taking stock of the situation around us, for more than a
century conditions have not been better or more promising for our
country than they are today," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"China's remarkable achievements are recognized all around the
world," he emphasized. "Our country has bright prospects from
which Hong Kong is sure to benefit."
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive said Hong Kong had finally broken free from
the psychological constraints brought about by the colonial era,
noting that "we should have the courage to set aside past modes of
thought and plan Hong Kong's long-term future with new vision."
</P>
<P>
"We the people of Hong Kong have begun to write our own
history," he said, stressing that as the motherland's economy,
culture and spirit develop and as the world continues to progress,
the Hong Kong people "will rise to the challenge of this brave new
era." 
</P>
</TEXT>
