<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Revenue Surplus Plunges 36 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The revenue surplus for the first
seven months of the year in Macao dropped 36 percent from the same
period of last year, the Macao Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
By the end of July, the revenue balance had declined 310
million patacas (about 39.24 million U.S. dollars) from the same
period last year, it quoted data from the Macao Currency and
Foreign Exchange Supervision Department as showing.
</P>
<P>
The total revenues increased only 0.7 percent to nearly
five billion patacas (about 632.9 million U.S. dollars), while the
total expenditures increased 4.8 percent to 4.7 billion patacas
(about 594.9 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
It showed that the tax revenue from casinos rose four
percent only. Casinos contribute nearly half the revenue income in
Macao.
</P>
<P>
While foreign trade remained brisk for the past months, other
leading economic sectors, including tourism and related
industries, suffered a blow this year due to security problems
over the past few months, observers said.
</P>
<P>
But expenditure kept rising. The cost for the rising salary of
civil service increased 10 percent, and government's expenditure
in buying goods and service rose 13.2 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
