<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Set Up First Coal-Fired Power Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh Power Development
Board (BPDB) has undertaken a scheme to set up a coal-fired power
generating station at Barapukuria in an effort to solve the
country's power shortage, sources from the BPDB said today.
</P>
<P>
This project was taken up as part of the BPDB's "Power System
Master Plan" which was approved by the government in August 1995.
</P>
<P>
The production of coal in Barapukuria in the northern part of
the country would start at the end of 1999 and about 1 million
tons of coal is likely to be produced from the mine annually, out
of which 700,000 tons will be used for running the power station.
</P>
<P>
Natural gas, furnace oil and high-speed diesel are now being
used for generating electricity in Bangladesh, whose only
hydropower plant, the Kaptai Power Station, meets just a fraction
of the demand for electricity.
</P>
<P>
Badly-needed power stations could not be set up in the northern
and western regions of the country to meet the growing demand for
power due to the lack of fuel locally, the sources pointed out,
adding that if local mineral resources are used, the production
cost of power will be lowered considerably.
</P>
<P>
Recently several coal deposits have been discovered in the
northern part of Bangladesh, including the Barapukuria Coal Mine,
which is the first to be undertaken for development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
