<HEADLINE> Perkins Misses Chance to Defend 400m World Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Kieren Perkins Wednesday
finished fifth in the 400-meter freestyle final in the Australian
national swimming championships in Brisbane, losing the chance to
defend his world title in Perth in January.
</P>
<P>
Daniel Kowalski, the silver medalist behind Perkins in the Rome
Worlds in 1994, also missed a place in the event after finishing
third.
</P>
<P>
Teenagers Grant Hackett took the first place by clocking three
minutes 46.85 seconds, the second fastest time in the world this
year. It was three seconds ahead of 14-year-old Ian Thorpe.
</P>
<P>
Perkins, who broke the 400 meters world record in Rome, is also
the world record holder and Olympic champion over the 1,500
meters. He will contest that event on Saturday and it is his last
chance of making the team for the world championships.
</P>
<P>
Kowalski is already on the 200 metres relay team but has not
got an individual place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
