<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Parties Feud on Slush Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 8 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's ruling New Korea
Party (NKP) and main opposition National Congress for New Politics
(NCNP) began a new round of feud on alleged secret funds.
</P>
<P>
Kang Sam-jae, secretary-general of the NKP, accused in a news
conference Tuesday that the NCNP's leader Kim Dae-jung had stashed
away 67 billion won (about 75 million U.S. dollars) in slush funds.
</P>
<P>
Kim and his party immediately denied the charges, saying the
allegations are nonensial and groundless.
</P>
<P>
A reminder of the slush funds which finally put former
presidents Chun Doo-hwan and Roh Tae-woo into the jail, Kang's
allegations sent a shock wave through the political community.
</P>
<P>
Political observers say the allegations are the NKP's first
broadside in a life-or-death struggle with the NCNP for winning
the presidential election only two months away.
</P>
<P>
Saying the NKP had evidence to back up his claims, Kang called
on the prosecution to launch an investigation into Kim's finances.
</P>
<P>
But while the prosecution said it had no reason at this time to
launch a probe, NCNP officials said they will take legal action
against the NKP secretary-general for libel.
</P>
<P>
"This is part of the ruling camp's desperate campaign to smear
our leader as the NKP's presidential candidate Lee Hoi-chang's
public approval ratings are running low," said NCNP spokesman
Chung Dong-young.
</P>
<P>
Kim is leading the four candidates in all opinion polls while
the NKP's Lee trails by Kim by at least 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Political observers believe that with his current popularity
among voters and barring a big scandal, Kim will be able to win
the December 18 presidential election, the fourth bidding for Kim.
</P>
<P>
The allegations, however, if found to be true, could seriously
damage Kim's popularity and his candidacy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sinhala Commission Report Rekindles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Heavy media debate has been
going on and a string of demonstrations have been held in Sri
Lanka since the Sinhala Commission published its Interim Report
that criticized the peace package initiated by the government.
</P>
<P>
About 800 monks from all over Sri Lanka prayed for the peace
process at a gathering in the center of Colombo Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
But their views were not shared by other Buddhist monks. On the
same venue, a sit-in protest was held on September 30 by some 200
monks to show their support for the Sinhala Commission.
</P>
<P>
The Interim Report, which was published on September 17, said
the devolution proposals and the draft constitution would endanger
the future of Buddhism and lead to the break-up of the country.
</P>
<P>
It said Sri Lanka should remain a unitary state for all time.
</P>
<P>
The commission asked the government to retain full control over
legislation, administration of justice, police forces, state land,
harbors and airports and archaeological sites.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, it recommended that the National Joint Committee
(NJC) should call on the people to reject the devolution package,
saying the Sinhala people, as well as the sovereignty and
territorial integrity of the country are facing grave dangers.
</P>
<P>
The Sinhala Commission was appointed two years ago by the NJC,
which groups 56 professional, religious and other associations, to
examine the injustice directed to the Sinhala community since Sri
Lanka won its independence in 1948.
</P>
<P>
The 12-member commission comprises former judges of the Supreme
Court, professionals and intellectuals, whose strong influence
gives the non-official organization importance in Sri Lanka's
political arena.
</P>
<P>
The commission said the report was made after talking with all
walks of the Sinhala people in the country, including Buddhist
clergy, intellectuals and politicians from both the government and
the opposition.
</P>
<P>
However, many argue that the report does not reflect the views
of those who support the devolution package of the government.
</P>
<P>
The peace package and the Draft Constitution of President
Chandrika Kumaratunga's Peoples' Alliance government seeks the
devolution of power through the establishment of a Union of
Regions, through which the government hopes to pacify the Tamil
community and end the 14-year-old ethnic war.
</P>
<P>
Under the package, more autonomy will be given to the Northern
and Eastern provinces, where Tamil rebels have been fighting a
guerrilla war for a separate state of their own since 1983.
</P>
<P>
The report of the commission has aroused strong public debate
in newspapers and other media. Demonstrations were held either by
the people supporting the devolution package or by those opposing
it.
</P>
<P>
Within the government opinion is divided as to whether the
proposals should be drastically changed or even abandoned.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman and Media Minister Mangala Samaraweera has
stated that the Sinhala Commission's report should be "consigned
to the dustbin of history" and described it as "the biggest
conspiracy against the Sinhala people."
</P>
<P>
His remarks added fuel to the already heated debate and a
demonstration was called in Colombo on September 30 to press an
apology from him.
</P>
<P>
While the minister insisted that he would never bend to any
mounting pressure, Agriculture Minister and General Secretary of
the ruling People's Alliance D.M. Jayaratne urged the
Parliamentary Select Committee to hear and consider the views of
the Sinhala Commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
