<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin Stresses Sino-US Economic, Trade Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 8 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin said
today that great progress has been made in Sino-US relations
over the past year, especially in bilateral economic and trade
co-operation.
</P>
<P>
Both China and the US should continue their efforts to ensure a
long-term and stable development of bilateral economic and trade
relations, he said during a meeting with visiting US Commerce
Secretary William Daley.
</P>
<P>
Daley is visiting China as the guest of Wu Yi, Chinese minister
of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation. The two ministers
co-chaired the 11th Session of the Sino-US Joint Committee on
Commerce and Trade (JCCT), which opened in Beijing Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The present level of bilateral economic and trade relations has
resulted from concerted efforts of the governments and business
communities of both countries, and indicates that the economies of
the two countries can supply each other's needs, the leader said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China and the US share extensive common interests
and have enormous co-operation potential in safeguarding the world
and regional peace, and in furthering co-operation in such
sectors as economy, trade, culture, science, technology and
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that governments and leaders of both
countries will take a broad and long-term view, take the overall
situation into consideration and work together to bring a
"healthy, stable and ever-growing Sino-US relationship" into the
next century.
</P>
<P>
On China's economic development, Jiang said that China will
unswervingly step up economic restructuring, open wider to the
outside world and develop a socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
As the world's largest developing country, China is ready to
make still greater contributions to the world's economic
prosperity, he said.
</P>
<P>
Daley described Sino-US relations as one of the most important
bilateral relations in the world. US President Clinton and the
American people are looking forward to President Jiang's upcoming
state visit to the US, he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief the visit will certainly push bilateral
ties up to a new level.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the present session of the JCCT, an important
meeting before President Jiang meets with President Clinton later
this month, is both positive and constructive.
</P>
<P>
The US side is willing to push forward bilateral economic and
trade cooperation together with the Chinese side by making full
use of the present momentum in the development of bilateral
relations, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
