<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sharp Recovery for Malaysia's Stocks, Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Share prices on the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange closed broadly higher today following a
sharp recovery in the country's currency -- the ringgit.
</P>
<P>
The Composite Index, which jumped to a high of 845.56 in
mid-afternoon, closed at 836.60 points, 33.15 points or 4.12
percent higher than Tuesday's close.
</P>
<P>
The Emas Index jumped 8.68 points to 235.18, the Industrial
Index surged 70.31 points to 1,716.55 and the Second Board soared
10.09 points to 434.25.
</P>
<P>
Gainers pounded losers by 670 to 70 while 74 counters closed
unchanged and 71 other counters were untraded today.
</P>
<P>
The main board ready turnover expanded to 333.556 million
shares worth 1,460.591 million ringgit (about 456.434 million U.S.
dollars) from 204.143 million shares valued at 768.430 million
ringgit (about 240.134 million U.S. dollars) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The second board volume increased to 59.396 million shares
worth 507.491 million ringgit (about 158.590 million U.S. dollars)
from 49.823 million shares valued at 469.672 million ringgit
(about 146.772 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Off market deals amounted to 31.592 million shares worth
293.631 million ringgit (about 91.759 million U.S. dollars) from
25.813 million shares valued at 267.035 million ringgit (about
83.448 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
An analyst said, "The market now is poised for a pre-budget
rally. Players are bullish on the deputy prime minister's (Anwar
Ibrahim) statement that the 1998 budget would address current
financial crisis effectively."
</P>
<P>
The 1988 budget is to be tabled in Parliament on October 17.
</P>
<P>
On the local foreign exchange market, the ringgit settled at
3.1750/50 to the U.S. dollar today against 3.2700/50 Tuesday on
rumors that the International Monetary Fund (IMF) will aid all
Southeast Asian countries affected by the current currency
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
A dealer said rumors were circulating that the IMF will inject
3.0 trillion U.S. dollars to help these countries which were
gravely affected since the speculative attack.
</P>
<P>
He said these affected currencies are now finding the "right
footage" before they stabilize.
</P>
<P>
The local unit also strengthened against other major
currencies. Against the Japanese yen, ringgit ended 2.5997/00 per
100 yen from 2.6825/29, against the Deutsche mark at 1.8049/85
from 1.8616/49, against the pound sterling at 5.1530/18 from
5.2892/06 and against the Singapore dollar at 2.0372/49 from
2.0975/66.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
