<HEADLINE> China's Petrochemical Industry Expanding Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 8 (Xinhua) -- China's National Petrochemical
Corporation (SINOPEC) has established co-operative relations with
companies and financial institutions in 50 countries and regions,
the "People's Daily" overseas edition reports today.
</P>
<P>
From 1991 to 1996, SINOPEC exported 3.37 million tons of
petrochemicals valued at 710 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
To make up for crude oil shortages on the domestic market, the
company has gotten enterprises in coastal areas and along the
Yangtze River to refine imported crude oil and opened processing
businesses supplying materials.
</P>
<P>
SINOPEC has also publicized its exportable technology and has
exported products to the United States, Italy, and other
countries.
</P>
<P>
Catalytic cracking technology exported by SINOPEC was tested by
a US company this September for a petrochemical plant in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
When China's petrochemical industry expanded with the reforms
and opening up, many overseas petrochemical companies invested in
China or looked for co-operation with Chinese petrochemical firms.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, SINOPEC had raised 8.356 billion US dollars
in overseas funds via various channels for a number of state
petrochemical projects.
</P>
<P>
It has also set up 152 Sino-foreign joint petrochemical
ventures, involving a total investment of two billion US dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
