<HEADLINE> Singapore's Manufacturing Output Increases in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's manufacturing
output increased 6.5 percent in August compared with a year ago,
while the cumulative output for the first eight months of this
year was about one percent higher over the same period in 1996,
the Economic Development Board (EDB) said today.
</P>
<P>
It said that the chemicals industries continued its high output
in August scoring an increase of 30.1 percent. The cumulative
output for the first eight months of 1997 grew 15.5 percent with
the petrochemicals as the main contributor.
</P>
<P>
The output of petrochemicals was 101.1 percent higher in
August, arising from the significant expansion in capacity of
several petrochemical plants, bringing the cumulative output up
57.7 percent for the first eight months of the year.
</P>
<P>
The output of electronics products rose 3.7 percent in August,
lower than the nine percent growth recorded in July. Disk drives
output still registered healthy growth, though growth rate was
lower than previous months, the EDB said.
</P>
<P>
It said that higher output in telecommunication products and
semiconductors was negated by declining output of personal
computers and consumer electronics. The cumulative output for the
first eight months of 1997 registered a marginal decline of 0.5
percent compared with the same months of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The EDB also said that export demand lifted up output in the
machinery industry by 10.2 percent, for there were more deliveries
of machinery to overseas buyers in August. In the meantime, the
transport equipment industry grew 13.4 percent with higher output
from both the marine and aviation segments.
</P>
<P>
The EDB also noted that output of fabricated metal products and
rubber/plastic products continued to decline 8.3 percent and 0.9
percent respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
