<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Action on Environment Protection Inadequate: ESCAP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The chief of the United Nations
Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP)
said here today that action to protect the environment in the
region has been "inadequate and slow."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening of the Fourth Session of the ESCAP
Committee on Environment and Sustainable Development, Adrianus
Mooy, executive secretary of ESCAP, said industrialization and
consumption in the region have not changed much and are still
largely unsustainable.
</P>
<P>
He added that exhaustion of natural resources, caused by
population growth, harmful agricultural practices, urbanization
and poverty, is still a matter of grave concern.
</P>
<P>
Mooy highlighted the environmental aspects of coal-based energy
and its efficient use for economic growth. He urged participants
to study how the region's growing energy demand could be met and
how the environmental impact of coal production and use can be
eased.
</P>
<P>
Thai Minister of Science, Technology and Environment Yingphan
Manasikarn said on the occasion that to address environmental
issues effectively, Asia-Pacific countries need regional and
international support in the form of technical assistance,
funding, capacity building and transfer of environmentally sound
technologies.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day meeting, the committee will discuss
refinement and promotion of methodologies for integration of
environment and development, environmental aspects of coal-based
energy and its efficient use, and environmental management of
mineral resources development.
</P>
<P>
At the panel discussion this afternoon, participants discussed
ways to set standards and goals for environmental quality, when
monitoring and enforcement capabilities are lacking in many
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Several speakers recommended that economic instruments and
other fiscal measures be used as powerful tools for promoting
environmentally sound human behavior. Besides, environmental
legislation management standards, environmental reporting, natural
resource accounting, and fiscal policy tools are also important
measures in the protection of the environment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Propose Special Market for Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said today that Malaysia will propose that a
specific market be set up for currency trading.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has been given the responsibility by the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank to handle efforts to come
up with regulations for currency trading.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that the establishment of a specific market for
currency trading was very important because the method used now
was not transparent and was open to abuse for the purpose of
manipulation and speculation.
</P>
<P>
"We know that all trading have specific markets. There is a
place to sell shares as well as commodities, there is a place to
sell anything and traders must be registered. But we find that in
currency trading there is no specific market and we do not know
who is trading," he told reporters at the Parliament House lobby
here.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has been voicing the need for supervision and
transparency in foreign currency trading because in its view, the
lack of these mechanisms had allowed for the currencies of certain
countries to be attacked by manipulators and speculators for their
own gains.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the mandate bestowed by the IMF and the World
Bank had given fresh impetus to Malaysia in its quest for more
transparent currency trading so that it could not be easily
manipulated.
</P>
<P>
He said that his Deputy, Anwar Ibrahim, who is also Finance
Minister, had been given the responsibility to come up with the
proposals, including regulations deemed able to curb manipulative
and speculative activities in currency trading, he said.
</P>
<P>
"One of his proposals is sure to be that we must have a
specific market where these currency traders can register
themselves and get a seat number. If they want to trade they go
there and we know who is trading, where the money comes from, how
much credit they get from the bank. We must know all this because
only then can we trade," he said when asked what form the specific
market suggested should take.
</P>
<P>
He said the fact that the currency trading practiced now was
completely hidden was acknowledged by the money traders
themselves.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that with the lack of transparency in hedge fund
transactions, there appeared to be some double standards here when
some quarters had called for openness and transparency while for
some people including international financier George Soros, they
could undertake transactions secretively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
