<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> To Improve People's Well-Being, Top Priority: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, Chief Executive
 of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR), today
promised to improve well-being of the SAR people, describing it as
 the top priority for his government to improve housing, education
 and care for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
"I realize from the outset that this (the question of housing)
is a highly complex problem," said the Chief Executive while
delivering his first policy address before the Provisional
Legislative Council this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He stated: "I set my administration three main targets: to
build at least 85,000 flats a year in the public and private
sectors; to achieve a home ownership rate of 70 percent in ten
years; and to reduce the average waiting time for public rental
housing to three years."
</P>
<P>
Achieving these targets will be a considerable challenge, Tung
said, stressing that "my administration has responded vigorously
to the challenge." The Financial Department of the SAR government
has set up a special task force to attack the problem, known as
the Steering Committee on Land Supply for Housing.
</P>
<P>
The SAR government will provide 120 hectares of land for
private housing up to March 1999, and an additional 260 hectares
in the following three financial years, he said. There will be
about 285 hectares of land for public sector housing over the same
 period, he added.
</P>
<P>
To meet the growing demand from more international
professionals operating in Hong Kong, 117 hectares of land
sufficient for at least 9,000 large flats, will be sold before
March 2002 in addition to the 64 hectares already included in the
sales program up to March 1999, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the need of major improvements to the
transport infrastructure for ensuring that all suitable land can
be used for housing, and the focus will be on high capacity,
environmentally friendly railway and road systems.
</P>
<P>
"Education is the key to the future of Hong Kong," Tung said,
noting that "our education system must be firmly rooted in the
needs of Hong Kong, must enable us to contribute to the
development of our country and must give us an international
outlook."
</P>
<P>
He said the SAR government will allocate 5 billion HK dollars
to establish a Quality Education Development Fund and will raise
recurrent expenditure on basic education by 7.6 percent in the
coming year.
</P>
<P>
"Caring for the elderly is the responsibility of every
family: we need to provide a sense of security, a sense of
belonging and a feeling of health and worthiness," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that for the elderly to feel secure, they must
first be financially secure.
</P>
<P>
"We will establish the Mandatory Provident Fund Schemes in 1998
 so that in 20 to 30 years all the workforce will have provision
for their retirement," he said, adding that the SAR government
will increase monthly payment for the elderly by 380 HK dollars in
 the next financial year.
</P>
<P>
More important for the elderly than cash is a place to call
home and the effective delivery of other good services, he pointed
 out.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
