<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Replace Firefighters in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian government
today decided to replace in stages its firemen fighting the forest
fires in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Housing and Local Government Minister Ting Chew Peh said this
was decided by the Cabinet which discussed the haze situation and
efforts by the Malaysians to douse the forest fires in Sumatra and
Kalimantan.
</P>
<P>
The government is very concerned with the well-being of the
Malaysian firemen there and also that of their families, he told
reporters here.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the replacement exercise would begin in the
next few days and the Fire and Rescue Services Department had been
alerted.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,200 Malaysia firefighters went to Indonesia in late
September to help the Indonesian authorities deal with the fires
which are blamed for the haze blanketing several countries in the
region including Malaysia, Brunei and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Ting said the number of Malaysian firefighters in Kalimantan
would be increased from 200 to about 500 and the figure in Sumatra
would be reduced from 1,000 to less than 800.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysians were reportedly successful in putting out 80
percent of the fires in the areas assigned to them.
</P>
<P>
Responding to questions, he said the replacement exercise would
not jeopardize firefighting operations in Malaysia which has more
than 8,000 firemen.
</P>
<P>
The minister praised the private sector for their contributions
towards helping local firemen in Indonesia and hoped that more
would come forward to offer generous donations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
