<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar ended
stronger today cheered by the Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA)'s
silence on interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The RBA board met Tuesday to consider monetary policy and in
the current climate of easier policy foreign exchange market
participants had feared its members might have given the go ahead
to lower the 5.0 percent cash rate today.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 72.47 U.S. cents up from 72.30
previously.
</P>
<P>
"The market bought it initially on the no-rate-move decision by
the RBA from the low of 72.30 U.S. cents to these level," said
Rothschild Australia trader Paul Macarounas.
</P>
<P>
Many market participants believe that other windows of
opportunity for a rate cut remain, either after key jobs data
tomorrow or following third quarter inflation release on October
22.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, Australian dollar ended at 88.66 up from
88.14 against the Japanese yen and at 1.2761 up from 1.2689
against the German mark.  
</P>
</TEXT>
