<HEADLINE> HKSAR Govt to Resolve Boat People Issue: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) Tung Chee Hwa said the
SAR government is developing strategies to resolve the remaining
aspects of Vietnamese boat people problem as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Tung said in his first Policy Address, which was delivered here
this afternoon, that for over 20 years Hong Kong has played an
outstanding part in coping with the burden of Vietnamese boat
people.
</P>
<P>
So far 143,000 refugees have been resettled to third countries,
69,000 migrants and illegal immigrants have been repatriated to
Vietnam. Today only 1,300 refugees and 800 migrants remain in Hong
Kong, to which recently have been added about 1,000 illegal
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
"We have done our part as citizens of the world. It is time to
bring this issue to a close one way or another," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the SAR government is pursuing arrangements with the
Vietnamese authorities to secure a faster pace of repatriation.
</P>
<P>
"We are pressing the United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR) and the international community to work harder to
arrange for resettlement of the remaining 1,300 refugees," he
said. "We will also continue to press the UNHCR to repay the debt
that is owed to Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
He said in pursuit of these objectives, the SAR government has
the full support of the Central People's Government. Tung himself
will also be urging the British government to discharge its
continuing moral responsibility to assist in reaching a full
solution to this problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
