<HEADLINE> FDI Projects Become New Point of Growth of China Economy: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The input of foreign direct
investment (FDI) has accelerated the economic development in China
with FDI projects becoming a new point of growth of the national
economy, a Chinese official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Of the total 297,000 approved FDI projects as of August this
year, over 145,000 have started operation, employing more than
17.5 million people, said Hu Jingyan, deputy director general of
the Foreign Investment Administration under the Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a China Investment Policy Seminar organized by the
ministry, Hu said, in 1996 the actually paid-in foreign capital of
FDI projects made up close to 15 percent of the national total
investment in fixed assets.
</P>
<P>
He said that the gross trade value of FDI enterprises reached
137 billion U.S. dollars in 1996, up 25 percent over the previous
year and making up 47 percent of the gross value of national
commodity import and export.
</P>
<P>
"The introduction of FDI has accelerated the national
industrial restructuring, renovated a large number of state-owned
enterprises, improved the efficiency and level of national
industry, and fostered the national economy," the Chinese official
stressed.
</P>
<P>
With the further deepening of reform and opening and further
perfection of the market economic structure, FDI enterprises will
play a bigger role in the development of the national economy, he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, since 1993 China has been the country with
the most FDI among the developing countries for four years in a
row, and ranked second in the world after the United States.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, held in conjunction with the '97 China (Hong Kong)
Investment Symposium, was aimed at explaining to local investors
the latest investment environment and policies of China's interior
areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
