<HEADLINE> Pakistani PM Calls for Rational Approach for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif today underlined Kashmir as the root cause of tension in
South Asia and said peace and stability will remain a distant
dream unless the leaders of the region display restraint and adopt
a "rational approach."
</P>
<P>
Sharif made the remarks in his note of thanks for an address by
British Queen Elizabeth II, who is on a six-day visit to Pakistan,
at the joint sitting of the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The British Queen called upon the leaders of Pakistan and India
to show a high degree of statesmanship for the resolution of
contentious issues between them through talks.
</P>
<P>
"Reconciliation will take time but the effort must be made,"
she said. "I am convinced it will be worthwhile for the more than
one billion inhabitants of the two countries."
</P>
<P>
Sharif agreed with the Queen on that statesmanship is required
for the resolution of the problems of South Asia.
</P>
<P>
"Unless the leaders of this region display similar wisdom and
self-restraint and adopt a rational approach, South Asian peace
and stability will remain a distant dream," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is, therefore, imperative to remove the main cause of the
tension that has afflicted South Asia for the last half a
century," he said, referring to the Jammu and Kashmir dispute with
India.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said Pakistan has taken the initiative to resume the
dialogue with India, hoping that India will reciprocate "our
sincerity by seriously addressing the Jammu and Kashmir question
and other outstanding issues in a structured and comprehensive
manner."
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, true peace has been a stranger to South Asia,
the storm clouds of tensions have dominated the political
landscape of South Asia for far too long, the root cause is the
unresolved core issue of Jammu and Kashmir," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The pledge must be redeemed and the atrocities against the
people of Kashmir must be brought to an end," he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani prime minister also underscored the plight of the
people of Afghanistan as a saga of human suffering, saying no
country in the world has suffered more from the tragedy of
Afghanistan than Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"We, therefore, have a vital interest in the restoration of
durable peace in that country," he said.
</P>
<P>
He assured full support to the U.N. efforts to promote an
inter-Afghan dialogue aiming to establish a lasting peace in
Afghanistan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
