<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Policies of Central Government Not Applied in HK: Chinese Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The economic and trade
legislation, policies and administrative measures of the central
government applicable to enterprises of China's inland will not be
applied to Hong Kong, a senior Chinese official reassured here
today.
</P>
<P>
The central government will not interfere in the economic and
trade affairs that fall within the high autonomy of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), An Min, assistant minister
of foreign trade and economic cooperation, told a China
investment policy seminar.
</P>
<P>
He described the application of the central government's
policies as "stopping at Luohu (Lo Wu) Bridge", which is situated
between the inland and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
After Hong Kong's return to the motherland, new forms of
cooperation will emerge in trade and economic areas between the
inland and Hong Kong on its original firm basis, expanding to new
areas and rising to higher levels, the Chinese official predicted.
</P>
<P>
To greet the early arrival of this date, the "one country, two
systems" principle should be unswervingly followed and the Basic
Law should be applied in a serious manner, to consolidate Hong
Kong's status as an international trade, finance, shipping and
information center, An Min said.
</P>
<P>
"The economic and trade relations between the two sides shall
further develop in accordance with international economic and
trade rules," he continued.
</P>
<P>
According to him, measures should be taken to fully guarantee
the participation of Hong Kong in multilateral and bilateral
economic and trade activities. As a separate customs region, HKSAR
may maintain and develop economic and trade ties with other
countries and regions independently in the name of "Hong Kong,
China", he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that China will renew efforts to improve the investment
environment of the inland and, in particular, will adopt measures
to encourage more investors to the midwest of China.
</P>
<P>
China's inland has become the world's second largest recipient
of foreign investment, with significant contribution from Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
Between 1979 and 1996, Hong Kong accounted for 99 billion US
dollars, or close to 60 percent of the inland's utilized foreign
capital, making it the largest investor in the inland.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was organized by the Chinese Ministry of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation to keep local businessmen informed
of the latest investment environment and policies of the inland,
with speakers coming from the inland's key economic-related
ministries and commissions.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was held in conjunction with the '97 China (Hong
Kong) Investment Symposium which, entering its fourth year,
brought a record total of some 900 investment projects from 29
provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
