<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR to Set Up Commission on Strategic Development, Tung Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The government of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) will set up a commission
on strategic development, with an aim to "keep up with" world
trends in competitive terms, said Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Delivering his first policy address before the Provisional
legislative Council, Tung said that Hong Kong's development
strategy will be based on two principles -- a free market economy
and a prudent fiscal policy.
</P>
<P>
He said: "Together with our emphasis on adding value, these
principles will uphold Hong Kong's competitiveness, maintain the
lifeblood of Hong Kong's economic development, and protect the
interests of every citizen."
</P>
<P>
"As this is an important issue with far reaching consequences,
the SAR government will set up a commission on strategic
development," Tung said, "I will be the chairman, and members of
the commission will include government officials, members from
industrial, commercial, financial and grass roots sectors, and
also academics."
</P>
<P>
According to him, the commission will be tasked to conduct
reviews and studies on Hong Kong's economy, human resources,
education, housing, land supply, environmental protection, and
relations with the motherland, to ensure that Hong Kong's
resources are well used, that Hong Kong keeps up with world trends
in competitive terms, and that Hong Kong maintains the vitality of
its economic development.
</P>
<P>
"We should have the courage to set aside past modes of thought
and plan Hong Kong's long-term future with new vision," Tung said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Leader Outlines Top Tasks for His Government (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) Tung Chee Hwa today
described it as "the most fundamental task" for his government to
promote the well-being of the people, stressing the need to build
Hong Kong into a more prosperous and stable region.
</P>
<P>
Delivering his 42-page policy address in the building of the
Provisional Legislative Council this afternoon, Tung pointed out
that Hong Kong's prosperity and stability are closely linked with
those of the motherland and expressed his determination to
implement the "one country, two systems" principle.
</P>
<P>
"To promote the well-being of the people is the most
fundamental task of a responsible government," he said. "We must
work to build Hong Kong for ourselves and for future
generations: a Hong Kong that is civilized, prosperous, stable and
democratic, filled with a new vitality."
</P>
<P>
Tung outlined in his first policy address the priorities of his
 government in the future work as follows:
</P>
<P>
-- Increase supply of land and build supporting infrastructure
to ensure that the target of constructing at least 85,000 flats a
year will be met, and build new major railways and new major
roads;
</P>
<P>
-- Set up a Quality Education Development Fund with 5 billion
HK dollars to finance innovation in education, develop centers of
excellence in universities and review education structure,
curriculum and examination system;
</P>
<P>
-- Increase monthly payments for the elderly by 380 HK dollars,
 set up 12 elderly health centers in 1998-99 to provide preventive
 and curative services, and provide additional 23 social centers
for the elderly in 1998-2002;
</P>
<P>
-- Reform training and retraining programs to make workers more
 responsive to market needs and provide new courses to equip
workers for tomorrow's industries;
</P>
<P>
-- Build up Hong Kong's information infrastructure and
implement a 5-year information technology education strategy to
enhance teaching and learning;
</P>
<P>
-- Provide 50 million HK dollars to the Service Support Fund to
 help improve service industries, provide 100 million HK dollars
for promoting tourism, and construct the Science Park, the Second
Industrial Technology Center and the Fourth Industrial Estate;
</P>
<P>
-- Establish closer cooperation with the inland areas'
authorities on infrastructure and environmental planning and start
 a waste reduction program in 1998;
</P>
<P>
-- Conduct a review of health care in 1998 and bring into
service additional 754 hospital beds;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Leader Outlines Top Tasks for His Government (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- Continue to provide job training and retraining and services
 to help new citizens find employment;
</P>
<P>
-- Continue to prepare for the legislative elections scheduled
for May 1998;
</P>
<P>
-- Further improve services of the government officials and
employees to "promote the objective of managing for results";
</P>
<P>
-- Continue to sustain the rule of law and independent
judiciary, and improve police's professional training and
efficiency in combating crime and corruption.
</P>
<P>
Tung said Hong Kong has "incomparable advantages" such as: a
high-degree autonomy under "one country, two systems", abundant
financial reserves, social and economic systems that work well,
and a sound, comprehensive legal system.
</P>
<P>
"We are the southern gateway to China and an international
financial, trade and shipping center. Our future economy will also
 be strongly supported by the rapid development" in the inland
areas, he added.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the need for Hong Kong to "keep up with world trends
in competitive terms" and "maintain the vitality" of its economic
development, Tung said, "The SAR government will set up a
commission on strategic development" for this reason and he
himself will be its chairman.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive said that the policy of reform and opening
up in the motherland has given new energy to Hong Kong's
development. "The 15th Congress (of the Chinese Communist Party)
under the leadership of President Jiang Zemin has just set out the
 goal of building China into a major power by the middle of the
21st century," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the prospects of the overall economic development of
Hong Kong and the motherland are bright, stressing the need for
Hong Kong and the inland areas of the motherland to raise their
cooperation to "new heights."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Hong Kong's return to the motherland on July 1,
he said: "We the people of Hong Kong have begun to write our own
history. Each step we take today will set our course for decades
to come."
</P>
<P>
As to the "one country, two systems" principle, he said that
Hong Kong and the motherland share the same fundamental
interests. "This is the basis for successfully implementing 'one
country, two systems'. It is also the starting point for the SAR
government when formulating policies for our relationship with
the motherland, and strategies for Hong Kong's long term
development," the Chief Executive said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he continued, the Basic Law gives "solemn and
inviolable legal protection for the "one country, two systems"
principle.
</P>
<P>
"In years gone by, the people of Hong Kong, mostly Chinese,
have created the miracle that is Hong Kong.... I sincerely hope
that each and every one, with the same sense of responsibility and
 commitment that we have towards our own families, will join hands
 to achieve our goals as we move steadily forward," Tung
concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
