<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Chief Executive Vows to Maintain Economic Vitality (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) Tung Chee Hwa today
pledged that his administration will strive to improve the
environment for business in Hong Kong and maintain its economic
vitality.
</P>
<P>
Delivering the first Policy Address of the SAR before the
Provisional Legislative Council this afternoon, Tung said the
government's efforts will be directed to increasing Hong Kong's
external competitiveness, increasing friendliness to business
within Hong Kong and to promoting a healthy competitive
environment.
</P>
<P>
"We will do everything to remove obstacles and constraints to
business development. We will give the private sector freedom to
set its own direction, to explore and to seize opportunities," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Talking about business friendly environment, Tung said Hong
Kong already has one of the world's most business friendly tax
regimes, the government's intention is to keep the tax regime
simple, predictable and competitive. Related government units are
also working closely with the private sector to cut red tape,
reduce costs of compliance and improve services.
</P>
<P>
He said that 98 percent of Hong Kong's businesses, employing
about two thirds of the workforce, are small enterprises. The
government is working on a scheme to help small and medium
enterprises seek loans from commercial banks to finance
pre-shipping activities.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that the government will work to improve Hong Kong's
position as a premier financial center by maintaining a world
class supervisory regime without over-regulation, by providing
state-of-the-art financial infrastructure and a well trained,
adaptable workforce, and by maintaining the rule of law, a low and
predictable tax regime, an open market and a level playing field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Chief Executive Vows to Maintain Economic Vitality (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tourism, which is Hong Kong's major earner of foreign exchange,
will continue to be stressed in government programs, he said. The
government will extend a loan of 100 million HK dollars to the Hong
Kong Tourist Association to start up an International Events Fund,
designed to bring together private sector partnerships to stage 50
major international events here over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
While stressing that the manufacturing industry should not be
neglected, Tung pointed out that innovation, adapting to new
technologies and developing new industries will always be
important for Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"We stand ready to inject up to 500 million HK dollars into the
Applied Research Fund, specifically to support the
commercialization of research in information technology and other
high technology fields," he said.
</P>
<P>
"My aim is to make Hong Kong an innovation center not just for
ourselves, but for South China and the region, adding value to our
economic hinterland, from which in turn we draw benefit," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will ensure land supply for a number of
scientific and industrial developments.
</P>
<P>
The government will take more effective enforcement actions
against all forms of infringement against intellectual property
rights, especially the sale of pirated and counterfeit goods, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that key to Hong Kong's economic efficiency and
international competitiveness is openness and competitiveness
within Hong Kong's economy, and the SAR government is fully
committed to promoting competition.
</P>
<P>
In terms of overall economic development of the SAR and the
mainland, prospects are bright, he said, adding that with Hong
Kong's return to the motherland and with the government support,
the relationship between Hong Kong and the mainland should
flourish comprehensively in all fields such as economy, finance,
trade, transport, culture, education, science and technology,
tourism and sports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
