<HEADLINE> Relocation At China's Three Gorges Reservoir Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The relocation of local people
from the Three Gorges Reservoir area in central China's Hubei
province is going as planned.
</P>
<P>
Four county seats in Hubei, one in the Chongqing Municipality,
and part of 19 towns will be inundated when the Three Gorges Dam
is completed. By early November, the present water level of 78 m
in the dam area will climb to 82.4 m.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges project is scheduled to cut off the main
stream of the Yangtze River from November 6 to 8. Navigation on
the main stream stopped yesterday morning when a canal on the
southern bank was opened.
</P>
<P>
Construction of a new county seat for Zigui, the home of a
great poet of ancient China, Qu Yuan (340B.C. - 278B.C.), and for
Badong has been completed.
</P>
<P>
Some party and government organizations of Zigui County have
started office work in the new county seat near Maoping Town. A
total of 2,600 people from the county seat of Badong have moved
out of the Three Gorges Reservoir area and settled in new
residential quarters in the new county seat.
</P>
<P>
Work on new county seats for Wushan, Fengjie and Yunyang is
still going on. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
