<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese People Say No to Divorce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The vast majority of Chinese men
and women frown upon the idea of getting a divorce despite the
rising divorce rate, according to a recent survey.
</P>
<P>
The survey of more than 6,000 couples in the cities of Shanghai
and Harbin, Guangdong and Gansu provinces was conducted by the
Shanghai Sociology Institute under the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
It shows that 89 percent of the respondents "never thought of
divorce".
</P>
<P>
Some 0.7 percent of those surveyed replied that they often
"want to divorce" his/her spouse, while 10 percent said they had
the desire to divorce "sometimes" or "occasionally".
</P>
<P>
Among those who want to have a divorce, 41.2 percent thought
that "the price for divorce is too high, and I won't take the
risk".
</P>
<P>
Some 11.1 percent said they would calmly accept their
spouses' request for a divorce, while 13.3 percent said they "may
accept it with calmness".
</P>
<P>
A study showed that ten out of 100 married couples got divorced
in the 1990s, compared with five at the end of the 1970s.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
