<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Electronic Nautical Chart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, October 8 (Xinhua) -- China's first electronic nautical
chart, namely, software that contains hundreds of nautical charts
and a large amount of navigation information, is being installed
on seagoing ships.
</P>
<P>
The new chart was invented by Harbin Engineering University,
according to Hao Yanling, head of a research group, to make sure
that ship captains could check course, port, or beacon information
promptly, instead of laboriously looking through many books and
charts as in the past.
</P>
<P>
The electronic chart also analyses information from satellite,
Hao says, "If you want to calculate the distance between the ship
and any point, the only thing you have to do is to draw a line on
the computer screen, and you get the correct figure immediately,"
along with course, speed, wind speed, and other information.
</P>
<P>
If the ship is on a wrong heading or there is an obstacle
ahead, the monitoring system will warn the ship.
</P>
<P>
Some experts say that when connected with the operational
system, the electronic chart can automate navigation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
