<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Province Increasing Agriculture Cooperation with Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Taiwan investors have more than
1,500 agriculture-related projects in Fujian province on the east
coast of China, involving nearly a billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Luo Fuzhi, from Taiwan, spent 300,000 US dollars last year
raising fish on 6.6-ha of leased land in Fujian's Zhangpu county,
and he is not worried about returns because the fish are doing
well.
</P>
<P>
Another investor put 20 million yuan into a 33-ha fish raising
base with 208 ponds in Fotan Township in the same county, and
produced 1.14 million fry in May, all of which are doing well.
</P>
<P>
Co-operation between Fujian and Taiwan began in 1985, and
Fujian has imported more than 1,500 new types of crops from
Taiwan, and some 400 pieces of produce-processing equipment, as
well as planting, breeding and processing technology.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the China Association for International
Exchange in Agriculture and Taiwan's Asia Agricultural Development
Center have held seminars on agricultural co-operation. More than
500 Taiwanese agronomists have visited Fujian, and 50 Fujian
experts have made a tour of Taiwan, to look for development
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
An imported type of watermelon has been planted on more than 60
percent of Fujian's watermelon acreage, and other varieties are
playing an increasingly important role in local agricultural
production.
</P>
<P>
In Zhangpu, Taiwan-funded agriculture-related projects
contributed 336 million yuan in output value, accounting for 21
percent of the province's total value in agricultural production.
</P>
</TEXT>
