<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Improving Pollution Treatment In Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The city of Guilin, one of
China's most famous scenic spots, in the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region, has expanded its waste water treatment to more than half
the waste water discharged every day.
</P>
<P>
The city has set up four waste water treatment plants, with a
total daily capacity of 180,000 tons, more than half the daily
waste water discharged by factories and residents, says Chen
Xiaoke, deputy director of the Guilin City Environmental
Protection Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The waste water treatment plants have put the city ahead of
other medium-sized cities in treatment capacity. The No.4
Treatment Plant is the largest in the province and is the first
urban infrastructure project built with foreign loans.
</P>
<P>
The plant was built at a cost of 106 million yuan (about 16
million US dollars) and has a daily capacity of 100,000 tons. It
went into operation in early 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
