<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Rules Out Currency Devaluation Possibility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's currency, the taka,
will not devaluate further in the wake of massive erosion in the
value of most Southeast Asian currencies, a local newspaper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
"I'm confident and sure that there will be no reflection of the
Southeast Asian (currency) crisis in Bangladesh," the Financial
Express quoted Finance Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria as saying
Tuesday at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister claimed that the economy in this South
Asian country is sound and is performing in full gear.
</P>
<P>
The minister asserted that the economy will be kept stable, and
there will be no change in the country's monetary policy or
exchange rate in the wake of the currency crisis in ASEAN (the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations) countries.
</P>
<P>
The minister said one reason that Bangladesh will not change
the exchange rate is that Bangladesh's trade relations with South
Asian countries are not as extensive as with countries in North
America and Europe.
</P>
<P>
There has also been no impact of the crisis in neighboring
countries like India and Pakistan, the minister pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Identifying currency convertibility in the capital account as
one of the reasons behind the crisis, the minister said that
Bangladesh is yet to make its currency convertible in the capital
account.
</P>
<P>
The economy of Bangladesh is performing well and growing
steadily despite disruptions caused by various problems like power
shortage, the minister stated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
