<HEADLINE> Passengers Carried by Thai Airways Decreases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The number of outbound
passengers carried by Thai Airways International (THAI) in fiscal
1997 dropped by 30 percent and inbound passengers by between 10-15
percent, THAI President Thamnoon Wanglee said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
While the exact figures of THAI's performance in fiscal 1997
are not yet available, it is estimated that judging by the drop in
the numbers of travelers to and from Thailand, THAI's profits
might have slid by 10 to 15 percent for fiscal 1997, which ended
on September 30.
</P>
<P>
The depreciation of the baht since July 2 had caused losses of
3.5 billion baht (95 million US dollars) in the last quarter of
fiscal 1997 alone, the Bangkok Post today quotes Thamnoon as
saying.
</P>
<P>
During fiscal 1996, the national flag carrier generated 78
billion baht (3 billion dollars) in income, with a 4.5 percent net
profit from the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Because of the depreciation of the baht and economic downturn,
Thais have refrained from overseas traveling.
</P>
<P>
Beginning October 1, THAI has raised its fares by 5 percent for
all classes on Japanese routes and for first and business class
tickets on flights serving the United States, while fares of all
classes to and from Europe, Australia and New Zealand have risen
by 3 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
