<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Makes Efforts to Develop Renewable Energy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government is
making great efforts to develop renewable energy, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The development of renewable energy gets great attention in the
national energy program and is aimed at providing energy
particularly in rural areas, Endro Utomo Notodisuryo, director
general for electricity and energy development, said here on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
As a tropical country, Indonesia is blessed with abundant
renewable energy resources such as bio-mass, solar energy, wind
energy and geothermal energy, the official said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the proportion of renewable energy in the
total energy supply is still insignificant, less than 0.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government has taken several measures to enhance
the production and utilization of renewable energy. They include
international cooperation to seek financial support, transfer of
technologies and exchange of information, market development and
tax exemption for renewable energy equipment, technical training
and lifting small power purchase tariff for private and
cooperative sectors.
</P>
<P>
Recently the government also launched a project aimed at
providing electricity to 1 million households within 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The growth of demand for energy in Indonesia in the recent 10
years was 10 percent per annum, higher than the 2 percent annual
growth of the world energy consumption, said Notodisuryo.
</P>
<P>
At present, about 80 percent of Indonesia's energy comes from
oil and natural gas, but coal, hydropower and solar power have
increased sharply in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Officials said that at present only 70 percent of Indonesia's
62,000 villages have electricity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
