<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Philippine Peso Further Slides Amid Sentiments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine currency of peso
has further slid during the past few days, breaking the
psychological mark of 35 pesos to one U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The peso depreciated to an average of 35.537 pesos per dollar
on Tuesday, hitting an intra-day record low of 35.981 pesos
despite the reimposition of a three-tired volatility band on
trading between the peso and the greenback.
</P>
<P>
The Bankers Association of the Philippines imposed a
two-percent volatility band starting Tuesday. According to the
rule, if the peso fluctuates beyond two percent of the reference
rate, the trading will be halted for 30 minutes. After resumption,
the band would be narrowed down to one percent and after three
recessions, the trading would be suspended for the whole day.
</P>
<P>
However, the rule backfired on Tuesday. The peso breezed down
by two percent to 35.625 pesos per dollar from 34.926 pesos per
dollar within half an hour of the start of trading.
</P>
<P>
After business was restarted, another vertical drop of one
percent soon brought the peso down to the all-time low of 35.981
pesos. The Central Bank was forced to step in to halt the slide by
selling U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The sharp depreciation of the peso also drew local bourses to
new lows. The 30-share composite index of the Philippine Stock
Exchange fell by 40.61 points to close at 1920.63 points after
declining 68.43 points on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the market failed to firm up because market
sentiments were for the peso to weaken due to many factors, one of
which is the rising demand for the dollar by companies importing
goods for Christmas and New Year.
</P>
<P>
Another important factor is foreign investors' confidence being
eroded by the country's quick changing of policies against the
current currency meltdown, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank imposed a 1.5 percent volatility band before
the regional financial turmoil and abandoned it on July 11 in the
face of sharp falls of the peso and other currencies.
</P>
<P>
To arrest the free fall of the peso, monetary authorities
tightened money supply in the market by raising the Central Bank's
overnight borrowing rate and commercial banks' liquidity reserve
rates to record highs, but then reduced them very quickly.
</P>
<P>
The changes signaled to the investors that Manila lacks
effective ways to handle the financial woes, analysts said.
However, monetary officials insisted that it is necessary to take
these steps.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that monetary authorities' actions also brought
about another grave and sensitive issue in the country. The
interest rates are soaring, making businessmen shy away from
borrowing money and the cost of production higher.
</P>
<P>
From only 14 percent on Wednesday last week, the average
interbank overnight loan rate has gradually climbed to Tuesday's
160 percent. The benchmark 91-day Treasury Bill rate also jumped
to 20 percent from 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
To ease the liquidity crunch that caused the higher interest
rates, the Central Bank has decided to reopen its overnight
lending facility starting today at a lower rate of 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
It stopped lending overnight funds two months ago to banks
which were suspected of making profits by using their excess funds
to speculate against the peso.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the right thing to do now is to regain the
investors' confidence through correct and stable policies.
Monetary authorities have expressed confidence that the country's
economy would survive the turmoil and become more healthy and
dynamic.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0246 </DOCNO>
