<HEADLINE> Ukraine May Raise Import Duties on Consumer Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Ukrainian government is
considering an increase in import duties on consumer goods by 2 to
2.5 percent in a bid to save the country's crumbling light
industry.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the parliament Tuesday, Ukraine's Industrial Policy
Minister Vasyl Gureev described the light industry situation as
critical. He said the production of light industry in 1996 was
only 16 percent of that in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Under a program to boost light industry production, the
government had pledged to spend 11.3 million hryvnas (6.1 million
U.S. dollars) on renovating the sector in 1996 and 55.9 million
hryvnas (30 million dollars) this year. But the sector received
only 510,000 hryvnas (276,000 dollars) in 1996 and none in 1997.
</P>
<P>
As a result, foreign-made commodities, including toilet tissues,
napkins, sausage, cheese and many other daily necessities, flooded
the Ukrainian market, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
In another move to reinvigorate the sector, the government and
the National Bank of Ukraine may offer long-term credit to
indigenous enterprises on preferential terms, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
