<HEADLINE> OECD Agrees to Admit Russia in Principle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Secretary-General of the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD)
Donald Johnston said here today that OECD has agreed in principle
to admit Russia but has not decided on when to grant the country
membership.
</P>
<P>
During a press conference, Johnston praised Russia's
achievements in establishing a market-oriented economy.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, Russia still has much to do and has to
complete all required reforms to standardize its economy before
its entry into the economic organization.
</P>
<P>
So it is still too early to talk of the exact date to
incorporate Russia as a OECD member, said Johnston, who arrived
here on Sunday for a working visit.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general said realizing a balanced budget and
formulating tax laws serve as a base for Russia's present reforms.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that there are some negative facts existing
in Russia's economic development, mainly slow privatization,
inefficient medium and small-sized enterprises, and an absence of
laws for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
OECD, headquartered in Paris, groups 29 countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
