<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary to Hold Referendum on Entry into NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Hungarian National Assembly
decided today to hold a referendum on November 16 on the country's
entry into the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
The referendum move was adopted by a two-third majority.
Opposition members of parliament withdrew from voting as a sign of
protest.
</P>
<P>
NATO decided in early July to admit Hungary, Poland and the
Czech Republic into the organization. Poland and the Czech
Republic will not conduct any referendum on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Hungary, however, declared at the start that it would hold a
referendum, but mainly to survey the public opinions on the
issue. The result of the ballot would have no bearings on the
government's policy on the nation's entry into NATO.
</P>
<P>
The government changed its original intention later under the
pressure from the opposition and declared that the result of the
poll would determine whether or not Hungary should join NATO.
</P>
<P>
The draft resolution on referendum also covered land purchase
by foreigners in addition to the NATO issue.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties opposed the phrasing of questions for the
referendum and deemed it necessary to hold separate referendums on
the two different issues.
</P>
<P>
Recently, they collected nearly 300,000 signatures, urging the
government to conduct a referendum on their requests.
</P>
<P>
Today, when the government put the draft resolution to vote,
all the opposition parties withdrew from the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Hungarian Prime Minister Horn Gyula said in a TV interview
Monday that there were no political or legal obstacles to the
referendum advocated by the government.
</P>
<P>
He accused opposition parties of setting obstacles to thwart
the smooth holding of the referendum as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Foreign Affairs Kovacs Laszlo said at the National
Assembly Tuesday that the referendum could not be postponed due to
the tight schedule. Otherwise, he said, Hungary would possibly be
excluded from NATO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0252 </DOCNO>
