<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in Myanmar Reaches 6.44 Bln Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Foreign direct investment (FDI)
in Myanmar reached 6.44 billion U.S. dollars by the end of
September this year, a Myanmar senior investment commission
official was quoted by today's The New Light of Myanmar as saying.
</P>
<P>
Maung Maung, secretary of the country's Foreign Investment
Commission and Minister at the Office of the Deputy Prime
Minister, said here Tuesday at the opening of a national workshop
on promotion of FDI in Myanmar that the commission has already
approved 279 foreign investment projects.
</P>
<P>
Leading investors are the United Kingdom, Singapore, Thailand,
the United States and Malaysia, he said.
</P>
<P>
The amount of FDI of the five ASEAN countries -- Singapore,
Thailand, Malaysia, Indonesia and the Philippines -- reached 3.15
billion U.S. dollars, accounting for 48.9 percent of the total FDI
in Myanmar, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
There are altogether 22 countries or regions investing in
Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar transferred from a centrally planned economic system to
a market-oriented one when it opened its door to the outside world
in late 1988.  
</P>
