<HEADLINE> Large Batch of Drug Seized in Northern Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Highway police in northern
Thailand Monday seized 598,000 amphetamine pills, a kind of
habit-forming stimulant, and arrested the man who transported
them, the Bangkok Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
It was the largest quantity of narcotic drugs seized so far
this year in the country, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Acting on a tip-off, highway police stopped a BMW car for a
search at a checkpoint in Phayao province in northern Thailand.
</P>
<P>
They found boxes of amphetamine pills, also known as "speed
pills" locally, in packets on the back seat.
</P>
<P>
The driver, Ilyas Maseng, 25, was then arrested. He said he had
been hired for 3,000 baht (81 U.S. dollars) to drive the car from
a BMW center in Chiang Rai to a client at a bus terminal in
Lampang province. Both provinces are in northern Thailand.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference on Tuesday, police said the seizure was
part of an ongoing narcotics suppression operation along the
country's northernmost border, which is often infiltrated by drug
smugglers from the opium-producing golden triangle.  
</P>
</TEXT>
