<HEADLINE> Myanmar Stresses Development of Industrial Zones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar leader Tin Oo stressed
the development of the country's industrial zones which are vital
for the growth of the industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
Tin Oo, second secretary of the Myanmar State Law and Order
Restoration Council, said at a coordination meeting here Tuesday
that scattering industries have been organized in the industrial
zones throughout the country, official newspaper The New Light of
Myanmar reported today.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar formed the Industrial Development Committee (IDC) in
July 1995 to strive for progress in the nation's industrial
sector.
</P>
<P>
Within two years' time, the IDC worked to establish industrial
zones, open industrial banks, amend patent laws, organize
industrial exhibitions and formulate plans for the development of
the industrial sector, Tin Oo said.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, industrial zones are being set
up in areas of Yangon, Mandalay, Bago, Myaungmya, Hinthada, Myeik,
Yenangyaung and Pyay.
</P>
<P>
Of the 17 industrial zones planned in Myanmar, those in the
capital of Yangon include Thanlyin-Kyauktan, Mingaladon,
Hlaingtharya, Dagon Myothit and Shwepyitha, of which the
Thanlyin-Kyauktan is being developed by Singaporean, Malaysian and
Italian-Thai entrepreneurs, while the Mingaladon by Japanese firms
and the Hlaingtharya by Thai investors.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar's growth rate of the
industrial sector was registered at 5.2 percent in the 1996-97
ended March over the previous year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
