<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Privatize Loss-Making State Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government is
determined to privatize the country's loss-making state-owned
enterprises (SOEs) as a matter of principle, not at under any
pressure, said well-informed sources from the Bangladesh
Privatization Board (PB) today.
</P>
<P>
The PB has already drafted a legal framework to be placed
before Parliament to pave the way for the government to privatize
the SOEs, PB Chairman Kazi Zafar Ullah stated Wednesday during his
dialogue with economic reporters.
</P>
<P>
The draft, the PB chief said, will be sent to the Ministry of
Law for its voting before being placed in Parliament so that all
hurdles could be overcome.
</P>
<P>
"We have laid the foundation of privatization," the PB chief
said, "Now the pace will be accelerated."
</P>
<P>
"We want to make units more profit-making and efficient," he
added, "We want to reduce our staggering losses of 434 billion
taka (about 977.47 million U.S. dollars) of different SOEs in last
25 years."
</P>
<P>
The PB has finalized 32 SOEs for privatization, the PB chief
stated, adding that out of those, the board has already issued
letters of intent for handing over nine SOEs.
</P>
<P>
Government shares of nine other SOEs are now being sold with
the approval of the prime minister, the PB chief continued.
</P>
<P>
The PB chief also emphasized the need for mobilization of
public opinion in favor of privatization and called for media
support and coverage in this regard.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
