<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haze Covers Indonesia's Capital, Official Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The hazardous haze caused by
forest fires in central and east Java is also affecting life in
Jakarta, capital of Indonesia, although its millions of residents
have not noticed it, an environmental impact control official
said.
</P>
<P>
The haze is hanging at an altitude of 3,000 feet above the
earth's surface, Nabiel Makarim, deputy head of the Environmental
Pollution Control Agency said here last night.
</P>
<P>
Based on satellite imaging records, the haze shrouding Jakarta
is quite thick and contains particles that may pose a threat to
the human respiratory system. "We all have to be careful," Makarim
said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, head of the National Meteorology and Geophysics Agency
Sri Diharto said the haze also covered the Sunda Straits, one of
the busiest water ways in the country.
</P>
<P>
He warned all airplanes and ships to stay alert while crossing
the Sunda Straits.
</P>
<P>
Due to the prolonged drought this year, fires have ravaged
about 300,000 hectares of forests in Sumatra, Kalimantan, Irian
Jaya and Java islands in the country.
</P>
<P>
The fires in the thick forests have generated dangerous
pollution levels in the affected areas and neighboring countries,
such as Malaysia, Singapore, the Philippines and Thailand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
