<HEADLINE> Southern Thailand Warned to Prepare For Smog Effects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Public Health Ministry
has warned people in southern Thailand to prepare to protect
themselves from the possible effects of the haze caused by forest
fires in Indonesia, press reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Children, the elderly and those suffering from allergies,
respiratory and heart problems should take extra precautions, the
ministry's Permanent Secretary Dr. Prakom Wuthipong was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The haze was blown into southern Thailand again by monsoon
winds after having faded away during the past few days.
</P>
<P>
The haze began to worsen late on Monday, with the level of
airborne particles reaching the hazardous limit of 120 micrograms
per cubic meter in Trang city and 90 micrograms per cubic meter in
Songkla city overnight, Prakom said.
</P>
<P>
A Trang airport official said the morning flight from Bangkok
to Trang was canceled Tuesday because visibility was only 350
meters.  
