<HEADLINE> Former Sri Lankan President Found Guilty of Conspiracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Presidential
Commission of Inquiry has found former President Ranasinghe
Premadasa guilty of conspiring the assassination of
parliamentarian Lalith Athulathmudali in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the commission today quoted a report of the
commission submitted to President Chandrika Kumaratunga on Tuesday
as saying that without the former president's order, no one would
dare to carry out the assassination, in which Athulathmudali was
shot dead on April 23, 1993.
</P>
<P>
The commission suggested to indict three other persons
including Western Provincial Council Member U.L. Seneviratne, who
were believed to be involved in the murder of Athulathmudali.
</P>
<P>
The commission also found former cabinet minister Sirisena
Cooray guilty of refusing to appear before the commission for
hearing. It therefore recommended Cooray be deprived of his civic
rights for seven years.
</P>
<P>
Athulathmudali initiated a motion of impeachment against the
then president Premadasa while he was a minister in Premadasa's
cabinet in 1991. He later formed the Democratic United National
Front.
</P>
<P>
He was shot dead while addressing a political rally in Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Premadasa was himself assassinated a week later while
participating in a May Day parade.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
