<HEADLINE> Italian PM Urges Support for Proposed Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi
Tuesday appealed to his Communist allies in parliament not to
bring down the government over proposed welfare cuts in the 1998
draft budget.
</P>
<P>
Reforming the welfare state "is the last and indispensable step
on our march toward Europe," Prodi told Parliament in a nationally
televised speech.
</P>
<P>
He said however the proposed budget was open to further
discussion.
</P>
<P>
The government says the budget cuts are needed to reduce
Italy's deficit, and thus allow the country to meet the criteria
for participation in the European Union's single currency, set to
debut in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Communist Refoundation, who won only 8 percent of the vote in
the last election but had the balance of power in the lower house
of parliament, says the 1998 draft budget measures cut too deep
into social welfare and pension benefits, and don't do enough to
stimulate employment.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the Communist Refoundation Fausto Bertinotti had
indicated that his party would vote against the measures, a move
that could prompt a government crisis. 
