<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russians Survive six-month Ordeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Two Russians have landed in
Phuket, Southern Thailand, after six months adrift on their yacht
without food supplies, according to reports reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Vidimir Medvedev, 44, and his son Maxim, 14, said they had
survived on rain water and what they could catch after losing
their supplies and communication gear in an accident in the Indian
Ocean.
</P>
<P>
The Russians were found by two villagers on Sunday who took them
to a Phuket hospital where they were admitted.
</P>
<P>
At the hospital, Dr. Nauvarat Somnam quoted the Russians as
saying their yacht had struck a rock in the Indian Ocean while
heading from South Africa to Australia. They collected rain water
and used telecommunication antennae as spears and rods to catch
fish and prawns, she said.
</P>
<P>
They had set sail from Russia on August 1995 on an
around-the-globe trip in which they called at Japan, Canada, the
United States and South Africa. Their last port of call had been
Cape Town, South Africa, which they left on April 27.  
</P>
</TEXT>
