<HEADLINE> Maradona's Urine Sample too Small for DNA Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Diego Maradona's urine
sample is too small to be submitted for DNA tests, and the
legendary soccer star said Tuesday that somebody switched
his urine sample with an aim to ruin his career.
</P>
<P>
Maradona, who will celebrate his 37th birthday later this
month, was tested positive for "illegal substances" after the
match against Argentinos Juniors on August 24.
</P>
<P>
"There wasn't enough urine for a (DNA) test," Maradona's
lawyer, Hugo Wortman Jofre, told public after meeting with
investigating Judge Claudio Bonadio.
</P>
<P>
Bonadio, who has ruled that Maradona can continue playing until
his investigation is completed, later said he would ask forensic
experts if the urine sample could be tested by others with better
technology.
</P>
<P>
Maradona, who has confessed to indulge in drugs before the
August game.
</P>
<P>
His positive test stopped the fifth comeback of his
controversial career. Despite Bonadio's ruling to allow him to
play again, Maradona has missed Boca's last three games because of
a leg injury.
</P>
<P>
Maradona has twice received 15-month bans for drugs-taking. In
1991, he tested positive for cocaine while playing for Italy's
Napoli. In 1994, he was refused to compete in the World Cup after
testing positive for a cocktail of performance-enhancing drugs,
including ephedrine. 
</P>
