<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Acts to Arrest Soaring Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines will reopen its overnight lending window starting
today to ease the liquidity crunch that caused interbank call loan
rate to hit a record high of 160 percent on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Gabriel Singson, governor of the Central Bank, said the bank
will lend one-day funds at a rate of 15 percent, local newspaper
the Manila Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The bank stopped lending overnight funds to commercial banks
two months ago to curb speculative activities against the peso.
Monetary officials suspected that these banks were using their
excess funds to bet against the peso, Singson said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Central Bank will also bring down its
overnight borrowing rate, which jumped to a record high of 30
percent in July and August, from 14 percent to 12 percent starting
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank is also studying the possibility of cutting
banks' liquidity reserves beyond the scheduled one percent
reduction each on October 15 and November 15, Singson said.
</P>
<P>
The liquidity reserves, a portion of the reserve requirement on
a bank's deposits that can be used to purchase government
securities, currently stand at six percent.
</P>
<P>
Starting early last week, the Central Bank has been
intensifying its mopping up operations to make sure money supply
levels in the country are kept within the target of the
International Monetary Fund programs.
</P>
<P>
It increased its overnight borrowing rate from 12 percent to 14
percent or even higher, triggering a funds shortfall that led to
the surge in the cost of money.
</P>
<P>
From only 13.59 percent last Wednesday, the average interbank
call loan rates climbed to 35.28 percent on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark 91-day Treasury Bill rate also rose to a six-year
high of 20 percent on Monday from only 14.957 percent the previous
week.
</P>
<P>
Higher interest rates made businessmen shy away from bank
credits, or raised the cost of production. In the long run, they
will erode the country's economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
