<HEADLINE> Indonesia Begins Final Stage of Campaign to Eradicate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia entered a decisive
stage in eradicating polio when it began Tuesday the final phase
of a three-year national campaign to wipe out the disease.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Health Sujudi launched the final polio eradication
drive Tuesday, at Tanggamus regency, in Lampung province, aimed at
immunizing 22 million children under the age of five, reports
reaching here today said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is seeking a free-polio certificate from the World
Health Organization (WHO) which hopefully will be granted by 2003,
the minister said.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day drive, 286,000 immunization posts have
been set up at public locations like health centers, bus stations,
kindergartens and child care centers throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Since 1995, Indonesia has completed five national polio
immunization campaigns. Each year two campaigns are held.
</P>
<P>
Children under five years of age are administered polio
vaccines free of charge.  
</P>
</TEXT>
