<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, October 8 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The fifty-second session of the General
Assembly Tuesday afternoon concluded its general debate which
began on September 22.
</P>
<P>
A total of 176 member states addressed the session, which
included 18 heads of state, one Crown Prince, 14 prime ministers,
16 deputy prime ministers, 111 foreign ministers, four other
ministers and 12 chairmen of delegations.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. Defense Department has canceled the
laser test at a satellite because of weather and technical
problems and it may have no more opportunity to schedule another
time for test because of the lifetime of the target.
</P>
<P>
The department planned to fire a ground-based laser at an
elderly Air Force satellite, but Pentagon spokesman Mike Doubleday
said Tuesday that poor weather and technical glitches would likely
force the experiment to be scrubbed.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The World Bank Tuesday approved a 28.6 million
U.S. dollar loan for Russia's social protection implementation
program.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be used to develop an effective system of income
support and poverty relief to meet the needs of a market economy.
</P>
<P>
The program will cover the main areas such as child allowances,
unemployment assistance, social insurance, social assistance and
social protection.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The historic full-scale peace talks for 76 years on a
political solution in Northern Ireland got underway Tuesday at
Stormont, Belfast.
</P>
<P>
Eight political parties representing the minority Catholics,
who want unification with the Irish Republic, and majority
Protestants, who want to stay British, sat down together at the
start of what is expected to be of hard bargaining.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein, which seeks the end of British rule and
reunification with Ireland, is taking part in the talks for the
first time thanks to a ceasefire by the Irish Republican Army
(IRA) in July.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
MOGADISHU -- The anarchy and civil strife in Somalia are not
confined to the mainland of the country alone, but also occur
along the beach lines off Somali Coast which stretches more than
3,333 km, the longest in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Seven Somalis were wounded last week when fighting broke out
between local fishermen and four foreign fishing vessels off Ego
Beach, about 340 km north of the capital Mogadishu.
</P>
