<HEADLINE> Arafat, Netanyahu Meet on Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu met today for
their first talks in eight months on the stalled Middle East peace
progress.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports reaching here, the two leaders met
at the Erez checkpoint on the border between Israel and the Gaza
Strip.
</P>
<P>
"As far as I know, the meeting has begun," reports quoted an
unidentified Palestinian official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between the two leaders was the first since peace
talks were suspended in March after Israel launched a Jewish
settlement in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The peace process was thrown into a deeper crisis when Islamic
extremists launched a series of suicide bombings over the past few
months which have killed 24 Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting came after U.S. Middle East envoy Dennis Ross
arrived in the region on a mission to revive the peace process
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Netanyahu have not met since February 9 when they
held two hours of talks also at the Erez checkpoint. 
</P>
