<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Develops Means to Keep Freshness of Bottled Beer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, October 8 (Xinhua) -- China has developed a capsule to
use in bottled beer to extend the freshness from three or four
months to a half year or longer.
</P>
<P>
The patented technique, which helps keep the air out of beer,
is especially useful in rural and remote areas where oxidization
and deterioration of bottled beer has been a big problem. Under
ordinary conditions, bottled beer can be kept for three or four
months, and in summer it can be kept for only about 20 days.
</P>
<P>
The technique was developed by Yang Wenyuan, a senior
technician at the Nanjing Institute of Electronics, and Li Xuzhi,
an associate professor at a university in Nanjing, after more than
8,000 experiments over the past eight years.
</P>
<P>
With the capsule, oxygen in bottled beer can be reduced from
one milligram to 0.03 milligrams within two days. Experiments at
three large breweries in Shandong and Beijing showed that the
capsule does a remarkable job of preserving the freshness of
bottled beer.
</P>
<P>
One Nanjing company has started producing the new
capsules. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Surgeons' Achievement Recognized by Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Three Chinese surgeons received
the nation's Sackler Award for their outstanding achievements in
clinical research and practices yesterday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Yin Dakui, vice-minister of Health, called on all young and
middle-aged medical workers to follow their example serving the
people heartily and being dedicated to their profession, according
to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Each award winner received a medal and has been invited to the
United States for a two-week professional exchange.
</P>
<P>
The winners are 35-year-old Luan Jie from the Plastic Surgery
Hospital of the Chinese Academy of Medical Science, Wang Zhijun,
39, from the Plastic Surgery Department of the People's Hospital
in Liaoning Province, and Yang Songlin, 36, from the Changzheng
Hospital of the Shanghai No 2 Military Medical University.
</P>
<P>
The Sackler Award was established in 1984 by the Ministry of
Health and an American medical expert, the late A. M. Sackler.
</P>
<P>
Its purpose is to encourage young and middle-aged Chinese
doctors to work hard in clinical practice and clinical scientific
research and to provide academic exchanges in medicine between the
two nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
