<HEADLINE> Chang out of Singapore Open in First Round </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 7 (Xinhua) -- American Jonathan Stark upset
top-seeded Michael Chang in the first round of the Singapore Open
in straight sets on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The match was a repeat of last year's final. The defending
champion Stark, who is ranked 94th in the world, ousted Chang 7-6
7-6 to disappoint the 5,000 crowd, most of whom were supporting
the Chinese-American, who ranks second in the world.
</P>
<P>
Stark fired 12 aces, consistently attacked the net and
hitting winners on the crucial points, especially in the first
set tie-breaker when he swept Chang aside 7-1.
</P>
<P>
"There were not a lot of secrets out there, because this is
our ninth meeting," said Stark, who narrowed their head-to-head
score to 3-6.
</P>
<P>
Chang said:"His serve is obviously a major part of his game and
I didn't seem to return well. It's even more frustrating to lose
to the same guy in the same event under similar conditions".
</P>
<P>
Second-seeded Marcelo Rios swept aside American Justin
Gimelstob 6-2 6-4 in just 59 minutes to move into the second round.
</P>
<P>
Rios, playing in Singapore for the first time, broke Gimelstob
in the third game and regularly drilled fluent winners past the
American. 
</P>
