<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Per Capita GDP Growth in Southeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The economy of east China's
Fujian province has developed rapidly, with a per capita GDP
ranking seventh in China since the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
A study by the provincial government development study center
shows that Fujian's GDP has greatly increased since 1978, from 6.6
billion yuan (about 0.8 billion US dollars) to 260 billion in
1996, and its ranking from 22nd to 12th among provinces.
</P>
<P>
In 1978, its GDP accounted for only 1.8 percent of China's,
while in 1996, it was 3.83 percent.
</P>
<P>
Fujian's per capita GDP went from 273 yuan in 1978 to 8,136
yuan in 1996, and its ranking from 22nd to seventh. Its economy
made such rapid progress that its per capita GDP rose above the
national level and nearly caught up with Zhejiang, Guangdong and
Jiangsu provinces, whose economic growth is the highest in China.
</P>
<P>
From 1991 to 1995, Fujian's economic growth rate was 19.3
percent, making it first in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
