<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Damaged Grotto Repaired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LANZHOU, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Binling Temple Grotto in
northwest China's Gansu province, which was severely damaged, is
going to be repaired and reinforced by the Northwest Branch of the
Railway Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
Binling Grotto is on the upper end of the Liujiaxia Reservoir
and is one of China's oldest grottoes, with an inscription that
dates back to the Western Qin Dynasty and has tremendous artistic
and historic value.
</P>
<P>
The Liujiaxia Reservoir has caused more rainfall in the
vicinity, and rain water seeped into the grotto through crevices,
leaving the temple inside unstable. The rain water also
accelerated the weathering process and there are cracks in several
places, leaving some parts in very dangerous condition. It is
feared that if the structure is not repaired soon, it will
collapse and destroy the grotto.
</P>
<P>
The northwest branch of the Railway Research Institute is in
charge of the repair project and will reinforce the grotto and use
horizontal holes as drains for water flow, to lessen damage that
rain has done to the rock.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that this project will be finished by 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
