<HEADLINE> Mexico Denies Airline Leaving Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Mexican airline
denied today that it is leaving Colombia due to the security
problems related to drug traffickings over the past few months in
that South American country.
</P>
<P>
General Manager of Mexicana de Aviacion in Colombia, Marinao
Ortega, said, "the company does not have any intention to withdraw
from Colombia."
</P>
<P>
Mexicana de Aviacion flights between Mexico City and Santa Fe
de Bogota are sufficiently healthy, Ortega said.
</P>
<P>
Mexicana officials said Sunday they were considering the
suspension of flights to Colombia if the Colombian authorities
could not guarantee the security of the company`s airplanes which
have been used to transport drugs.
</P>
<P>
Ortega said, "There are certain presures for all airliners
traveling to this country, but these are security matters that
will be handled correctly."
</P>
<P>
The senior executive expressed his confidence that Colombian
authorities will take measures to prevent drugs from entering the
country through Mexican airplanes.
</P>
<P>
Mexicana de Aviacion schedules four 156-passenger flights a
week between the two capitals, which covers 50 percent of the
flights between the two countries. Another 50 percent is covered
by Colombia's Avianca.
</P>
<P>
About 31 kilograms of cocaine were discovered hidden in a
Mexicana airplane on the Bogota-Mexico City route last Tuesday and
a similar case was found in August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
