<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Re-employment in Northwest China Province Stepped up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Harbin, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Two years ago, when Xuan Wenjie
lost her job in Harbin, the capital of northest China's
Heilongjiang province, she broke down and cried -- but now, she
has become the boss of a wholesale market and has become quite
well known.
</P>
<P>
When the state-owned sector in this city started reforms,
300,000 workers found themselves out of work. In order to help
them find jobs, the local government made all possible
arrangements. It allocated re-employment funds and relief funds,
and provided job skill training. The labor department also set up
labor markets and job recommendation services.
</P>
<P>
There are over 200,000 laid-offs in Harbin who, like Xuan, have
found re-employment, accounting for 60 percent of all the jobless
workers in this celebrated old industrial base.
</P>
<P>
The local government also encourages private enterprises and
the service sector has become an important re-employment
channel. The government also supports increased state-owned
enterprise reforms, by offering help to workers, for example, to
open enterprises, and encourages workers to find jobs themselves.
</P>
<P>
Economists say that, with the going of reforms, unemployment is
inevitable, and how to solve the re-employment question is still a
problem.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
