<HEADLINE> Serb Leaders Urged to End Influence in TV, Radio Stations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Carlos Westendorp,
representative of the Dayton peace agreement, called for the
elimination of political leaders and party influence in the
operation of the Pale Radio and TV station, reported the Yugoslav
news agency Tanjug today.
</P>
<P>
In talks with Momcilo Krajisnik, a member of the presidency of
the Republic of Bosnia, Westendorp also urged Krajisnik to
withdraw from the station's management commission, saying it was
the precondition before the station's control and management were
restored.
</P>
<P>
However, in a speech to station staff members on strike today,
Dragan Kalinic, chairman of the National Assembly (parliament) of
the Republic of Srpska, accused the international community of
interfering in the republic's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The international community has no right to decide the
arrangement of personnel affairs. The right to appoint and remove
members of the working staff of the Pale Radio and TV station is
the responsibility of the Serb government of Srpska, the
parliament leader said.
</P>
<P>
Several hundred soldiers of the NATO-led Stabilization Force
(SFOR) last Wednesday seized two Serb radio and TV stations --
Banjuluka and Pale -- in a bid to silence propaganda hostile to
the Dayton treaty signed in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
The station's employees have been on strike since last Saturday
in protest against the SFOR's action, which was seen as another
sign of NATO's get-tough policy on Serb factions who are not
complying with the treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
