<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Recycling Waste in South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The long-imagined dream of
turning waste into cash became a reality recently in south China's
Guangzhou, where a new environmental protection project has
changed the city's disposal methods.
</P>
<P>
The city collects over 4,000 tons of garbage daily, and its two
major garbage dumps only have a 3 or 4-year capacity, so the city
was faced with a mounting garbage problem and decreasing dump
space.
</P>
<P>
However, the newly established Sanxin Fertilizer Plant, which
has a daily disposal capacity of 1,500 tons, is expected to ease
this pressure. It uses new technology to disinfect and sort the
garbage, recycling iron and steel, and using plastics, rubber, and
tires for petroleum and diesel oil, and remaining organic
materials to produce 167 varieties of fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
The plant can produce 50,000 tons of highly-effective
biological fertilizer annually, dispose of 5,600 tons of waste
plastic, and produce 4,000 tons of petroleum and diesel oil.
</P>
<P>
The city's Environmental and Sanitation Administration Bureau
is holding talks with an American company to establish a garbage
disposal plant with a daily capacity of 1,000 tons, which can
produce acetic acid and alcohol through a gasification process.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou spent 500 million yuan last year on the Datansha
Resources Power Plant, which generates electricity by burning 900
tons of garbage every day.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Quake Hits Central Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Another strong earthquake hit
central Italy earlier this morning, causing further damage to the
ancient basilica of Saint Francis of Assisi.
</P>
<P>
The latest quake, measuring 4.9 on the Richter scale, was
centered in the mountainous Colfiorito region on the borders of
Umbria and Tuscany, in the same area as the two stronger tremors
that occurred on September 26.
</P>
<P>
Officials said here there were no fatalities from the new
tremor that occurred at 01:24 (23:24 GMT Monday), but two women
were injured amid general panic.
</P>
<P>
Last month's quakes killed 12 people, left some 40,000 homeless
and caused damage to many historic buildings.
</P>
<P>
According to the monks of Saint Francis of Assisi, today's tremor
brought down more stones from the pediment of the basilica, whose
treasures include frescoes by Giotto and the 13th century painter
Cimabue.
</P>
<P>
The monks said the tremor also caused cracks in a ceiling of
the papal apartments. The September 26 earthquake brought down two
vaulted domes covered with frescoes by Cimabue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
