<HEADLINE> Government Firefighters Stop Raging Border Blaze </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Local firefighters have
controlled the fire raging across the Sino-Kazakhstan border in
northwesternmost China's Altay region, today's China Daily quoted
sources from Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region as saying.
</P>
<P>
"On Sunday afternoon, about 170 firefighters in Altay's Habahe
County put out the fire, which had crossed into the county's
Qibengde district on Saturday afternoon to form a 200-meter wide
fire belt, devastating more than 660 hectares of land, mainly
covered by grasses and shrubbery," Yin Juxian, an official with
the Xinjiang Meteorological Observatory said.
</P>
<P>
There was no immediate word of casualties.
</P>
<P>
Yin's observatory monitored by satellite a 2,600-hectare fire
that broke out in Kazakhstan on September 22.
</P>
<P>
Wind pushed heavy smoke into neighboring Altay from September
24 to October 1.
</P>
<P>
Residents in the 117,600-square-kilometer Altay, one of the
cleanest regions in China, complained that for the first time they
breathed polluted air.
</P>
<P>
According to Yin, Kazakhstan border authorities informed their
Chinese counterparts in Altay on October 2 that the overwhelming
fire might attack the vicinity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
