<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Upgrade Key National Synchrotron Radiation Lab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 8 (Xinhua) -- China plans to spend 125 million
yuan (15 million US dollars) in the coming four years to improve
synchrotron radiation experimental devices in a key national lab
located in Anhui Province, east China.
</P>
<P>
China's first synchrotron radiation light source was completed
in 1989 in the lab at the Chinese University of Science and
Technology located in Hefei, capital city of Anhui.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, five light beams and five experimental stations have
been established in the lab, receiving researchers coming from
more than 120 research institutions from both at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
A large number of key findings have been obtained related to
life sciences, micro-electronics, medicine and basic science
theories.
</P>
<P>
Improvements of the laboratory will be made mainly to extend
the working hours of light source system and raise the stability
of light beams, the lab's scientists said.
</P>
<P>
Synchrotron radiation light source plays a key role in the
research of basic theories and high technology, namely in the
fields of physics, chemistry, life sciences, new materials,
medicine, microscopy, and super integrated circuits.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
