<HEADLINE> Tunis and Osaka Win rights to Host Judo Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The International Judo
Federation's (FIJ) congress announced here on Tuesday that Tunis
and Osaka would host the 2001 and 2003 world championships
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Tunisia will be hosting their first ever championships while it
will be the fourth time that Japan has won the honour. Tokyo
hosted the event in 1956 and 1958 while Chiba had it in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 World Cup will be held in the Belarussian capital
Minsk after the Netherlands withdrew. France is to host the
Millenium Cup in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Congress also announced that the legendary Dutch judo
competitor Anton Geesink, a former world heavyweight champion,
and Briton Charles Palmer, a former President of the FIJ, had
been promoted to the highest level in judo of 10th dan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
