<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 52nd Session of General Assembly Concludes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The fifty-second session
of the General Assembly this afternoon concluded its general
debate which began on september 22.
</P>
<P>
A total of 176 member states addressed the session, which
included 18 heads of state, one Crown Prince, 14 prime ministers,
16 deputy prime ministers, 111 foreign ministers, four other
ministers and 12 chairmen of delegations.
</P>
<P>
From October 8, The session will focus its discussion on the UN
reform plan proposed by Secretary-General Kofi Annan in July.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before declaring its closure, President Hennadiy
Udovenko said the efforts by the Secretary-General to reform the
United Nations had obtained strong political support. All the
delegations welcomed the comprehensive reform package and most
supported its endorsement in principle.
</P>
<P>
The president said the general debate had demonstrated the
international community continued to concentrate its efforts on
the resolution to the most acute problems facing humankind. The
concern of the member states remained to be focused on the spots
of instability.
</P>
<P>
He said that the internationalization of such
problems as terrorism, drug trafficking, money laundering and
corruption, illicit arms trading, environmental pollution was also
placed at the center of the debate.
</P>
<P>
The general debate had also witnessed support for encouraging
human rights, democratization and good governance as well as
advancement of women and protection of the rights of children
and persons belonging to minorities, the president said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that promotion of economic and social progress,
eradication of poverty and ensuring the widest possible
participation in an expanding world economy, regional
integration and cooperation justifiably occupied a predominant
place in the general debate.
</P>
<P>
It was clearly stressed during the debate that the process of
globalization should lead to an increasing integrated approach to
development and should give benefits to all nations, added the
president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
