<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Sets Poverty Eradication Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations has
set October 17 as International Day for the Eradication of Poverty
due to the fact that global poverty remains widespread.
</P>
<P>
According to fact sheets issued by the U.N. Development Program
(UNDP) here today, almost one-third or 1.3 billion people live on
less than a U.S. dollar a day, the poverty line set by the World
Bank for international comparison.
</P>
<P>
UNDP also gave the following figures to alert the world to the
severity of the issue:
</P>
<P>
-- some 840 million go hungry every day and face food
insecurity;
</P>
<P>
-- well over a billion lack access to safe water;
</P>
<P>
-- nearly a billion are illiterate;
</P>
<P>
-- women comprise 70 percent of the world's poor;
</P>
<P>
-- nearly a third of the people in the least-developed
countries are not expected to live to the age of 40;
</P>
<P>
-- half of Sub-Saharan African population will live in absolute
poverty by 2000;
</P>
<P>
-- more than 100 million live in poverty in industrialized
nations;
</P>
<P>
-- in these countries 37 million are jobless;
</P>
<P>
"Unless the growth in impoverishment is halted, the gap between
the poor and the rich will widen further, challenging
international peace and security," UNDP said.
</P>
<P>
UNDP has allocated 60 percent of its core resources for the
least-developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Agreements to reduce poverty have been reached by global
conferences in the 1990s, among them the target of reducing severe
and moderate malnutrition by half among children under age five by
2000 from the 1990 level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
