<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Controversial Laser Test May Be Canceled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Defense Department
has canceled the laser test at a satellite because of whether and
technical problems and it may have no more opportunity to schedule
another time for test because of the lifetime of the target.
</P>
<P>
The department planned to fire a ground-based laser at an
elderly Air Force satellite, but Pentagon spokesman Mike
Doubleday said today that poor weather and technical glitches
would likely force the experiment to be scrubbed.
</P>
<P>
Testers first tried to fire the Army's Mid-Infra Advance
Chemical Laser, or MIRACL, on Saturday, but a software breakdown
thwarted the attempt. They made a second effort last night, but
the test was again canceled because of poor weather over the White
Sands Missile Range in New Mexico, Doubleday said.
</P>
<P>
Since the target satellite's battery is fading rapidly, the
test may be canceled, and no future tests have been scheduled. The
military does not have another near-obsolete satellite on which to
experiment.
</P>
<P>
"There is some question that there will be any further
opportunities" for the test, Doubleday said.
</P>
<P>
Critics said that the experiment could mark a step toward
approval of space warfare technology. But Pentagon argued that the
test was to determine U.S. satellites' vulnerability, saying a
nation increasingly dependent on satellites must have the
technology to protect them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Credit Outstanding Up Modestly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Consumer credit outstanding
in the U.S. grew at a 4.2 percent seasonally adjusted annual rate
in August following a revised 5.9 percent increase in July, U.S.
Federal Reserve (Fed) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Fed report said that the level of auto credit in the U.S.
declined by 1.7 percent to 400.1 billion dollars in August from
400.7 billion in July, the first drop since March.
</P>
<P>
But the revolving credit, mainly the credit card loans,
expanded by 7.1 percent in the month to 523.8 billion dollars,
comparing with 520.8 billion in July.
</P>
<P>
Other consumer credit, which comprises all other loans not
included in auto and revolving credit, also increased by 7.3
percent to 304.8 billion dollars from 303 billion dollars in July.
</P>
<P>
Total U.S. consumer credit in August reached an seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 1228.7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report also revised downwards the increase rate of the
consumer loans in July from the 6.4 percent which was announced
early last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
