<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Steps up Air Patrol in No-fly Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Pentagon said on Tuesday
that U.S. air patrols in U.S.-imposed no-fly zone in southern Iraq
has increased as Iraqi aircraft continued to skirting over the
area.
</P>
<P>
"The numbers have gone up. Numbers of (U.S.) sorties have gone
up... last week," Captain Michael Doubleday, a Pentagon spokesman,
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said it was because "there have been violations of the
no-fly zone by Iraqi aircraft." The "violations" had taken place
in both northern and southern no-fly zones, "but primarily in the
south."
</P>
<P>
Iraqi aircraft would "risk getting shot down" if they fly over
the no-fly zones, Doubleday said. "We've done that in the past. We
stand ready to do it in the future. But I'm not in any position to
predict if and when that will occur."
</P>
<P>
Pentagon officials, speaking privately, said Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein appeared to have begun a new round of testing the
flight bans after Iranian F-4 fighters bombed one of Iranian
guerrillas' bases inside southern Iraq on Sept. 29.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, the United States ordered the aircraft carrier
Nimitz to said at a top speed to the Gulf, five days ahead of
schedule, as a warning to Iran for its violating the no-fly zone
in southern Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
