<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Swimming Coaches Charged in Doping Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Prosecutors in Berlin have launched
a lawsuit against two German swimming coaches in connection with
the alleged systematic doping of swimmers in former East Germany,
German press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Dieter Lindemann and Volker Frischke, both current German
Swimming Federation (DSV) coaches, have been formally charged by
prosecutors in the doping case, German news agency DPA quoted DSV
president Ruediger Tretow as saying today.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time since the 1990 German reunification that
criminal proceedings have been started against the systematic and
institutionally approved use of performance-boosting substances in
former East Germany, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Tretow disclosed that several current German national swimmers
had been cited as witnesses in the case.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the belief that the doping case was "only the
tip of the iceberg" and expected that more indictments would
follow.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Berlin prosecutors were currently
investigating 11 swimming coaches. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
