<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full-scale Talks on N. Ireland Get Underway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 7 (Xinhua) - The historic full-scale peace
talks for 76 years on a political solution in Northern Ireland got
underway today at Stormont, Belfast.
</P>
<P>
Eight political parties representing the minority Catholics,
who want unification with the Irish Republic, and majority
Protestants, who want to stay British, sat down together at the
start of what is expected to be of hard bargaining.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein, which seeks the end of British rule and
reunification with Ireland, is taking part in the talks for the
first time thanks to a ceasefire by the Irish Republican Army
(IRA) in July.
</P>
<P>
Ulster Secretary Mo Mowlam said the talks could be a "defining
moment" for Northern Ireland's future. Politicians had it within
their grasp to lay foundations for a peaceful and harmonious
future, she added.
</P>
<P>
"Today is a crucial day in that it is the start of the process
proper. It is a very weighty task which is on our shoulders
collectively," said Gary McMichael, leader of the pro-British
Ulster Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
Martin McGuinness, chief negotiator of Sinn Fein, said he hoped
the talks would "bring an end to conflict on this island".
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams also said in an interview
published in Spain today that he saw an unprecedented chance of
peace in Northern Ireland under the new Labor Government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
