<DOCNO> XIE19971008.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Campaign Finance Bill Stalled in Two Votes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate, entangled in
partisan infighting, dealt a serious setback Tuesday to
legislation to overhaul the system of campaign finance laws. Two
key procedural votes failed to gain enough support to advance the
legislative process.
</P>
<P>
Backers of the bipartisan bill, which is cosponsored by
Republican Senator John McCain and Democratic Senator Russell
Feingold, have been threatening to attach it to other major bills
pending in the Senate if they cannot pass it on its own.
</P>
<P>
The Republicans lost the first of the two procedural votes and
Democrats the second.
</P>
<P>
On the second of the two votes, the Senate voted 53-47 to push
the McCain-Feingold bill forward. That was seven short of the
number needed to force another, straight majority-wins vote on the
measure, but showed the bill's strength as eight Republicans
joined the 45 Democrats in supporting it.
</P>
<P>
Earlier majority Republicans failed, 52 to 48, eight fewer than
required, to advance a proposal that would make it harder for
unions to spend members' dues on political campaigns. The labor
movement spent large sum of money in the last election on behalf
of Democrats.
</P>
<P>
Senate Republican Leader Trent Lott said he thought the Senate
did the "right thing," in halting the McCain-Feingold bill in its
tracks because of what he said were constitutional problems with
the legislation.
</P>
<P>
Lott said, "The Senate has been provided more than adequate
debate on this bill."
</P>
<P>
But Democrats were furious that the only votes allowed were
procedural ones requiring 60 votes for passage.
</P>
<P>
"The bottom line is, the vast majority of Republicans are
refusing to allow this Senate to act on one of the most important
pieces of legislation to be brought up in this Senate, in this
Congress," said Minority Leader Tom Daschle.
</P>
<P>
McCain-Feingold supporters called Lott's union measure a
"poison pill," saying it was designed to ruin the legislation's
chances.
</P>
<P>
While all 52 votes in favor of the procedural motion to allow a
vote on Lott's amendment were cast by Republicans, three
Republicans joined the 45 Democrats in opposition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
